text: Immunodeficiency 60 is an autosomal dominant disease that encompasses both combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This disease also has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by variably decreased immunoglobulin production, decreased T-regulatory cells, overall impaired lymphocyte maturation, inflammatory bowel disease, and recurrent sinopulmonary infections, all of which are attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the BACH2 gene located on chromosome 6q15. Furthermore, Immunodeficiency 60 is exactly synonymous with BACH2-related immunodeficiency and autoimmunity, BRIDA, and IMD60.

Immunodeficiency 27a is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and is described as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by high circulating levels of IFNG, failure of cellular responses to IFNG, and early and often fatal mycobacterial infections. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IFNGR1 gene located on chromosome 6q23.3. Immunodeficiency 27a is also known by several exact synonyms, including IMD27A, autosomal recessive IFNGR1 deficiency, autosomal recessive MSMD due to partial IFNgammaR1 deficiency, autosomal recessive MSMD due to partial interferon gamma receptor 1 deficiency, autosomal recessive immunodeficiency 27A, mycobacteriosis, and autosomal recessive mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial IFNgammaR1 deficiency, as well as autosomal recessive mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial interferon gamma receptor 1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 27b is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease noted for residual cellular responses to IFNG in vitro and recurrent, moderately severe infections with environmental mycobacteria or Bacillus Calmette-Guerin. This condition is rooted in heterozygous mutations in the IFNGR1 gene on chromosome 6q23.3. Immunodeficiency 27b is also known by several exact synonyms, including IMD27B, autosomal dominant IFNGR1 deficiency, autosomal dominant MSMD (Mendelian Susceptibility to Mycobacterial Diseases) due to partial IFNgammaR1 deficiency, autosomal dominant immunodeficiency 27B, mycobacteriosis, and autosomal dominant mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial interferon gamma receptor 1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 11a is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, severe combined immunodeficiency, and a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by defective intracellular signaling in T and B cells, an increased number of transitional B cells, hypogammaglobulinemia, a decreased number of regulatory T cells, and defects in T-cell function. This condition is attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CARD11 gene located on chromosome 7p22.2. Additionally, immunodeficiency 11a is precisely synonymous with CARD11 deficiency, IMD11A, SCID due to CARD11 deficiency, and severe combined immunodeficiency due to CARD11 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 11b is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a T cell deficiency, which inherently has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a T cell deficiency marked by defects in T-cell activation, increased IgE, eosinophilia, and the early childhood onset of moderate to severe atopic dermatitis. This condition is due to a heterozygous mutation in the CARD11 gene located on chromosome 7p22.2. Immunodeficiency 11b is also exactly synonymous with IMD11B, atopic dermatitis, elevated IgE, and eosinophilia, as well as immunodeficiency 11B with atopic dermatitis.

Immunodeficiency 15b, also precisely known as IMD15B, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and severe combined immunodeficiency. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, immunodeficiency 15b is distinguished by an onset in infancy of life-threatening bacterial, fungal, and viral infections, failure to thrive, impaired differentiation and activation of immune cells, along with hypo- or agammaglobulinemia, yet relatively normal B and T cell numbers. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IKBKB gene located on chromosome 8p11.21.

Immunodeficiency 15a, also known exactly as IMD15A, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It is characterized by immune dysregulation, combined T and B cell deficiency, inflammation, and epithelial defects, which are due to a heterozygous missense mutation in the IKBKB gene located on chromosome 8p11.21. This condition is part of a broader category that involves diseases with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 26 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, severe combined immunodeficiency, and something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by virtually absent peripheral B and T cells but normal numbers of NK cells, a complete block in B-cell differentiation, and a defect in the slow repair of DNA double-strand breaks in fibroblasts, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PRKDC gene located on chromosome 8q11.21. Additionally, immunodeficiency 26 is precisely known as IMD26, SCID due to DNA-PKcs deficiency, immunodeficiency 26 with or without neurologic abnormalities, and severe combined immunodeficiency due to DNA-PKcs deficiency.
Combined immunodeficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease involving multiple components of the immune system.
Dendritic cell deficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, defined as a condition characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of dendritic cells.
B cell and dendritic cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency, which is characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of dendritic cells and B cells.
T cell, B cell, and NK cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency, which is characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of T cells, B cells, and natural killer (NK) cells.

Monocyte dendritic cell and NK cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency, which is defined as a combined immunodeficiency characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of monocytes, dendritic cells, and natural killer (NK) cells.

Immunodeficiency 54 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, NK cell deficiency, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe intra- and extrauterine growth retardation, microcephaly, decreased numbers of CD56(dim) natural killer cells, adrenal insufficiency, and recurrent viral infections. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MCM4 gene on chromosome 8q11.21. Immunodeficiency 54 is also known by exact synonyms including IMD54, NKCD, familial isolated natural killer cell deficiency, primary immunodeficiency due to MCM4 deficiency, and primary immunodeficiency with natural-killer cell deficiency and adrenal insufficiency.

Immunodeficiency 41 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of combined immunodeficiency. It is characterized by a defect in T cell regulation with the proliferation of CD8+ T cells, impaired antibody-specific responses, and elevated cytokines. This results in recurrent viral, fungal, and bacterial infections, lymphadenopathy, and variable autoimmune features. The disease has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL2RA gene on chromosome 10p15.1. Additionally, immunodeficiency 41 is known by several exact synonyms, including CD25 deficiency, IL2RA deficiency, IMD41, immunodeficiency 41 with lymphoproliferation and autoimmunity, immunodeficiency due to CD25 deficiency, and interleukin-2 receptor alpha chain deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 39, also known exactly as IMD39, is a type of autosomal dominant and primary immunodeficiency disease. It is characterized by a specific kind that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of Immunodeficiency 39 is a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by impaired interferon I and III production in response to influenza virus infection, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IRF7 gene on chromosome 11p15.5.

Immunodeficiency 10 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of T cell and NK cell immunodeficiencies. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a T cell and NK cell immunodeficiency marked by the onset in childhood of recurrent infections, attributable to defective T- and NK-cell function. This condition stems from a homozygous mutation in the STIM1 gene located on chromosome 11p15.4. Immunodeficiency 10 is also known by several exact synonyms including CID due to STIM1 deficiency, IMD10, STIM1 deficiency, combined immunodeficiency due to STIM1 deficiency, and immune dysfunction with T-cell inactivation due to calcium entry defect 2.

Immunodeficiency 18 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and something that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by onset in infancy or early childhood of recurrent infections with variable severity, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CD3E gene on chromosome 11q23.3. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 18 is exactly synonymous with CD3-epsilon deficiency and IMD18.

Immunodeficiency 19 is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, severe combined immunodeficiency, and is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by the onset in early infancy of recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections, featuring a T cell-negative, B cell-positive, natural killer cell-positive immune cell phenotype. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CD3D gene located on chromosome 11q23.3. Immunodeficiency 19 is also known by several exact synonyms, including CD3-delta deficiency, IMD19, SCID T cell-negative, B cell-positive, NK cell-positive, and severe combined immunodeficiency, T cell-negative, B cell-positive, NK cell-positive.

Immunodeficiency 17 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of T cell deficiency, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by partial T-cell lymphopenia with normal numbers of B and NK cells and highly variable clinical severity that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CD3G gene on chromosome 11q23.3. This condition is exactly synonymous with CD3-gamma deficiency, IMD17, SCID-like immunodeficiency, T cell-partial, B cell-positive, NK cell-positive, and immunodeficiency 17, CD3 gamma deficient.

Immunodeficiency 59 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, also known as a B cell and dendritic cell deficiency, which essentially indicates it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is characterized by granulocytopenia, B-cell and dendritic cell deficiency, recurrent septic infections of the respiratory tract, skin, and mucous membranes, as well as stress-induced hypoglycemia. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HYOU1 gene on chromosome 11q23.3. Immunodeficiency 59 is also exactly synonymous with IMD59, granulocytopenia with immunoglobulin abnormality, and immunodeficiency 59 and hypoglycemia.

Immunodeficiency 44, also exactly known as IMD44, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by increased susceptibility to viral infections and adverse multisystemic reaction to vaccination with apparent defects in mitochondrial fission and fusion that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the STAT2 gene on chromosome 12q13.3.

Immunodeficiency 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a T cell deficiency, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by early onset of recurrent infections due to defective T-cell activation, ectodermal dysplasia, and congenital myopathy. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ORAI1 gene, encoding a subunit of the plasma membrane calcium channel CRAC, located on chromosome 12q24.31. Immunodeficiency 9 is also known by its exact synonyms: CID due to ORAI1 deficiency, IMD9, combined immunodeficiency due to ORAI1 deficiency, and immune dysfunction with T-cell inactivation due to calcium entry defect 1.

Immunodeficiency 7, also known exactly as IMD7, TCR-alpha-beta-positive T-cell deficiency, and immunodeficiency 7, TCR-alpha/beta deficient, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a T cell deficiency. It is characterized by a decrease or absence of CD3+ T cells with TCR-alpha/beta expression, immune dysregulation, recurrent infections, and failure to thrive. This condition at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance, and more specifically, it is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRAC gene located on chromosome 14q11.2.

Immunodeficiency 65, which has exact synonyms IMD65 and immunodeficiency 65, susceptibility to viral infections, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by the onset in early infancy of recurrent and severe viral infections, an impaired cellular type I interferon response, and poor outcomes after vaccination with live attenuated vaccines. This is due to a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IRF9 gene on chromosome 14q12.

Immunodeficiency 49 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is also recognized as a T cell deficiency and is defined by its foundation in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by T cell lymphopenia, low T-cell receptor excision circles, impaired T-cell proliferative responses, alongside dysmorphic facial features, hypotonia, and severe global developmental delay. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BCL11B gene located on chromosome 14q32.2. Furthermore, immunodeficiency 49 is precisely synonymous with IMD49, SCID (T-cell negative, B-cell positive, NK cell positive), with intellectual disability, spasticity, and craniofacial abnormalities, as well as severe combined immunodeficiency (T-cell negative, B-cell positive, NK cell positive), with intellectual disability, spasticity, and craniofacial abnormalities.

Immunodeficiency 64, also precisely known as IMD64, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by a deficiency in T cells, B cells, and NK cells. This condition exhibits variably decreased numbers of T cells, with lesser deficiencies of B and NK cells, and decreased phosphorylation of the extracellular-signal-regulated serine kinase ERK in T and B cells. It manifests in early childhood with recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections. The material basis for this disease is at least partially attributed to autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RASGRP1 gene located on chromosome 15q14.

Immunodeficiency 43 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by recurrent infections, reduced serum concentrations of immunoglobulin G and albumin due to rapid degradation of these proteins, abnormal renal or liver function, and excessive gastrointestinal protein. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in B2M on chromosome 15q21.1. Immunodeficiency 43 is also exactly synonymous with B2M deficiency, IMD43, beta-2-microglobulin deficiency, and hypercatabolic hypoproteinemia.

Immunodeficiency 56 is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This condition is recognized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency marked by B- and T-cell defects including defective class-switched B cells, low IgG levels, impaired antibody response, and compromised T-cell responses to certain antigens, alongside variable dysfunction of NK cells. The underlying cause of this disease is attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL21R gene located on chromosome 16p12.1. Immunodeficiency 56 is also known by its exact synonyms: IL21R immunodeficiency, IMD56, and combined immunodeficiency due to IL21R deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 52 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of T cell deficiency, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a T cell deficiency characterized by the onset of severe recurrent infections in infancy and a defect in T-cell receptor signaling, resulting in variable immunological disorders. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LAT gene on chromosome 16p11.2. Immunodeficiency 52 is also known by its exact synonyms IMD52 and severe combined immunodeficiency due to LAT deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 58, also known precisely as IMD58 and severe combined immunodeficiency due to CARMIL2 deficiency, is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the umbrella of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiencies. It is characterized by a specific condition that essentially necessitates autosomal recessive inheritance. The disease is defined by its distinctive manifestation, which includes defective T-cell function with a decrease in Treg cells and deficient CD3/CD28 co-stimulation responses in both CD4+ and CD8+ T cells, a variable impairment in B-cell function, the occurrence of early-onset skin lesions, recurrent respiratory infections or allergies, and chronic persistent infections. The genetic underpinning for this condition is traced back to either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CARMIL2 gene located on chromosome 16q22.1.

Immunodeficiency 32B, also known as IMD32B, autosomal recessive IRF8 deficiency, and immunodeficiency 32B, monocyte and dendritic cell deficiency, autosomal recessive, is a type of autosomal recessive disease which specifically involves a deficiency in monocyte, dendritic cell, and NK (natural killer) cell. It is characterized by defects in the development or function of monocytes, dendritic cells, and NK cells leading to recurrent infections, particularly viral infections. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IRF8 gene located on chromosome 16q24.1. Moreover, immunodeficiency 32B is considered to have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 32a is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and a dendritic cell deficiency. It is identified by its basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The condition is defined as a dendritic cell deficiency characterized by a significant loss of CD11C-positive/CD1C dendritic cells and heightened susceptibility to mycobacterial infections, which stems from a heterozygous mutation in the IRF8 gene on chromosome 16q24.1. Immunodeficiency 32a is also known by several exact synonyms, including IMD32A, MSMD due to partial IRF8 deficiency, MSMD due to partial interferon regulatory factor 8 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial IRF8 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial interferon regulatory factor 8 deficiency, and immunodeficiency 32A, mycobacteriosis, autosomal dominant.

Immunodeficiency 13 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and T cell deficiency, which specifically involves a condition with a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by decreased CD4 T-lymphocyte counts due to a heterozygous mutation in the UNC119 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. It is also exactly synonymous with ICL, IMD13, and idiopathic CD4 lymphopenia.

Immunodeficiency 12 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of combined immunodeficiency characterized by decreased titers of specific antibodies and impaired T cells proliferative responses to mitogens. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MALT1 gene on chromosome 18q21.32. This condition, which is also precisely referred to as IMD12 and combined immunodeficiency due to MALT1 deficiency, is recognized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 35 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and it also has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infection after BCG vaccination and impaired cellular responses to IL-12, IFN-alpha/beta, IL-23, and IL-10, arising from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TYK2 gene on chromosome 19p13.2. Immunodeficiency 35 is known by various exact synonyms, including IMD35, TYK2 deficiency, autosomal recessive HIES with atypical mycobacteriosis, autosomal recessive hyper-IgE syndrome with atypical mycobacteriosis, susceptibility to infection due to TYK2 deficiency, and tyrosine kinase 2 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 30 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of T cell and NK cell immunodeficiencies. It is characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a T cell and NK cell immunodeficiency defined by the absence of responses to IL12 and IL23 in T cells and NK cells, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL12RB1 gene located on chromosome 19p13.11. Immunodeficiency 30 is also known by several exact synonyms including IMD30, MSMD due to complete IL12RB1 deficiency, MSMD due to complete interleukin 12 receptor beta 1 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to interleukin 12 receptor beta 1 deficiency, and Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete IL12RB1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 62, also precisely known as IMD62, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, B cell deficiency, and a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a B cell deficiency characterized by the onset in the late first decade of life of recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, impaired antibody response to vaccination, low levels of circulating memory B cells, and almost undetectable antibodies. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ARHGEF1 gene located on chromosome 19q13.2.

Immunodeficiency 53, also precisely known as IMD53, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiencies. This condition is characterized by recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, an increase in the CD4+ T cell to CD8+ T cell ratio, impaired T-cell proliferative responses to multiple antigens, and an impaired ability to produce specific immunoglobulins. The basis for this disease is either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RELB gene located on chromosome 19q13.32. It is noteworthy that immunodeficiency 53 fundamentally involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 55 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of combined immunodeficiency, which means it at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a combined immunodeficiency characterized by intrauterine growth retardation and a defect in DNA replication causing impaired immune cell differentiation in the bone marrow. This results in natural killer cell deficiency and chronic neutropenia. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GINS1 gene on chromosome 20p11.21. Immunodeficiency 55 has exact synonyms, including IMD55 and combined immunodeficiency due to GINS1 deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 45, also exactly known as IMD45, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of primary immunodeficiency diseases. This condition is characterized by a primary immunodeficiency disease that manifests through impaired control of the replication of certain viruses and a failure to develop an antiviral state in response to alpha-interferon or beta-interferon. The material basis for this condition lies in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IFNAR2 gene located on chromosome 21q22.11. Additionally, immunodeficiency 45 is recognized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 28 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and is characterized by its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease that leads to increased susceptibility to mycobacterial disease, elevated levels of IFNG in the plasma, and an absence of cellular response to IFNG. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IFNGR2 gene located on chromosome 21q22.11. Immunodeficiency 28 is also known by several exact synonyms, including IFNGR2 deficiency, IMD28, MSMD due to complete IFNgammaR2 deficiency, MSMD due to complete interferon gamma receptor 2 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete IFNgammaR2 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete interferon gamma receptor 2 deficiency, and immunodeficiency 28, mycobacteriosis.

Immunodeficiency 51 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a primary immunodeficiency disease, also characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by the onset of chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis in the first years of life and a lack of cellular responses to stimulation with certain IL17 isoforms, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL17RA gene on chromosome 22q11.1. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 51 is exactly synonymous with CANDF5, IMD51, and familial candidiasis 5.

Immunodeficiency 63 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of T cell and NK cell immunodeficiencies. It is described as a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular immunodeficiency is characterized by an increased number of NK cells but impaired differentiation of these cells and T cell abnormalities. Patients with this condition experience recurrent infections and abnormal activation of immune pathways, leading to lymphoid proliferation, dermatitis, enteropathy, and hypergammaglobulinemia. The cause of Immunodeficiency 63 is traced back to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL2RB gene located on chromosome 22q12.3. Immunodeficiency 63 is also known by its exact synonyms: IL2RB deficiency, IMD63, and Immunodeficiency 63 with lymphoproliferation and autoimmunity.

Immunodeficiency 66, also known exactly as IMD66, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease and a specific form of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The disease is defined by its onset in infancy, presenting recurrent bacterial infections and defective immune cell migration and chemotaxis, primarily affecting neutrophils, although other cell types may also be involved. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MKL1 gene located on chromosome 22q13.1-q13.2.

Immunodeficiency 61 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of B cell deficiency, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a B cell deficiency characterized by the onset in early childhood of recurrent infections due to an intrinsic defect in the ability of B cells to produce antibodies, a condition that arises from a hemizygous mutation in the SH3KBP1 gene on chromosome Xp22.12. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 61 is exactly synonymous with IMD61.

Immunodeficiency 34 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, phagocyte bactericidal dysfunction, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a phagocyte bactericidal dysfunction characterized by impaired respiratory burst in all types of phagocytes and increased susceptibility to infection by poorly virulent mycobacteria, which has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the CYBB gene on chromosome Xp21.1-p11.4. Immunodeficiency 34 is also known by several exact synonyms including AMCBX2, IMD34, X-linked MSMD due to CYBB deficiency, X-linked Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to CYBB deficiency, familial atypical mycobacteriosis X-linked 2, and immunodeficiency 34, mycobacteriosis, X-linked.

Immunodeficiency 50 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, which is also categorized as a combined immunodeficiency. This condition is partially defined by its material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized as a combined immunodeficiency with profound lymphopenia, hypogammaglobulinemia, poor immune response to vaccine antigens, fluctuating neutropenia, and the onset in early childhood of recurrent bacterial or varicella zoster virus infections. This condition has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the MSN gene on chromosome Xq12. Immunodeficiency 50 is known by several exact synonyms, including CID due to Moesin deficiency, IMD50, MSN-related combined immunodeficiency, X-linked Moesin-associated immunodeficiency, combined immunodeficiency due to Moesin deficiency, and immunodeficiency 50 X linked recessive.

Immunodeficiency 47 is categorized as a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type II, an X-linked recessive disease, and a primary immunodeficiency disease. It is specifically characterized by having a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance and exhibits a phenotype of abnormalities in immune system physiology. Immunodeficiency 47 is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease that is distinguished by liver dysfunction, recurrent bacterial infections, hypogammaglobulinemia, and defective glycosylation of serum proteins, which is due to a hemizygous mutation in the ATP6AP1 gene on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, it is also known by several exact synonyms, including CDG IIs, CDG2S, CDGIIs, IMD47, congenital disorder of glycosylation type IIs, and immunodeficiency and hepatopathy with or without neurologic features.

Immunodeficiency 33 is a type of combined immunodeficiency and an X-linked recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a combined immunodeficiency characterized by early-onset severe infection and variable immunological abnormalities that has its material basis in hemizygous mutation in the IKBKG gene on chromosome Xq28. Immunodeficiency 33 is exactly synonymous with IMD33, X-linked MSMD due to IKBKG deficiency, X-linked MSMD due to NEMO deficiency, X-linked mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to IKBKG deficiency, and X-linked mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to NEMO deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 71 is classified as an autosomal recessive disease and falls under the category of combined immunodeficiencies. This condition is characterized by a combined immunodeficiency that is notably marked by thrombocytopenia, impaired neutrophil and T-cell chemotaxis, reduced T-cell activation, and the early onset of recurrent infections and inflammatory features during infancy or early childhood. The disease's material basis is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ARPC1B gene located on chromosome 7q22.1. Furthermore, Immunodeficiency 71 is synonymously known as IMD71, PLTEID (Platelet abnormalities with eosinophilia and immune-mediated inflammatory disease), and Immunodeficiency 71 with inflammatory disease and congenital thrombocytopenia, indicating the disease's multifaceted impact on the immune system and its associated conditions.

Immunodeficiency 70, also precisely known as IMD70, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease that encompasses both T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by a decreased number of CD4+ T cells and CD19+ B cells, recurrent bacterial infections, and severe cutaneous warts on the hands, feet, and face. The underlying genetic basis for Immunodeficiency 70 is a heterozygous mutation in the IVNS1ABP gene located on chromosome 1q25.3. This disease exemplifies an instance where its material basis stems from autosomal dominant inheritance.

Immunodeficiency 69 (IMD69) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that specifically impacts T cells and NK cells. It is characterized by a heightened susceptibility to disseminated mycobacterial infection and a failure of T and NK cells to produce gamma-interferon upon in vitro stimulation. This condition fundamentally arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IFNG gene located on chromosome 12q15. Additionally, it is understood as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Growth hormone secreting pituitary adenoma 2 is a specific type of growth hormone secreting pituitary adenoma, characterized by adult-onset sporadic acromegaly and somatic somatotropinoma, with its material basis in a mutation in the GPR101 gene on chromosome Xq26.3. It is exactly synonymous with GH-secreting pituitary adenoma 2, PITA2, X-linked acromegaly, and acromegaly due to pituitary adenoma 2.

Pituitary adenoma 5 is a type of pituitary adenoma characterized by the development of different types of familial or sporadic pituitary adenomas. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CDH23 gene on chromosome 10q22.1. Moreover, pituitary adenoma 5 is also exactly synonymous with PITA5 and pituitary adenoma 5, multiple types.

Pituitary adenoma 1 is a type of pituitary adenoma characterized by different types of familial or sporadic pituitary adenomas that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in AIP on chromosome 11q13.2. Additionally, pituitary adenoma 1 is exactly synonymized with PITA1 and pituitary adenoma 1, multiple types.

Pituitary adenoma 3 is a type of pituitary adenoma characterized by the development of predominantly GH-secreting pituitary adenomas but also, in some patients, ACTH-secreting adenomas. This condition has a material basis in a somatic mutation in the GNAS gene located on chromosome 20q13.32. Furthermore, pituitary adenoma 3 is exactly synonymous with PITA3 and pituitary adenoma 3, multiple types.

Mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of keratosis, characterized by a bilateral mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma and periorificial keratotic plaques with severe pruritus of lesions. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including OLMS, Olmsted syndrome, mutilating palmoplantar hyperkeratosis with periorificial keratotic plaques, and palmoplantar and periorificial keratoderma.

X-linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of disease that falls under the category of mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques, which is characterized by its recessive inheritance linked to the X chromosome. Specifically, this condition is associated with a hemizygous mutation in the MBTPS2 gene located on chromosome Xp22.12. Moreover, it is acknowledged by the exact synonyms OLMSX and X-linked Olmsted syndrome, indicating its recognition under different names within the medical community. This condition is not only a specific manifestation within the broader classification of diseases with material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance but also distinctly identified by its genetic basis.

Autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a type of mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV3 gene on chromosome 17p13.2. This condition is also exactly synonymous with OLMS1, Olmsted syndrome 1, and autosomal dominant Olmsted syndrome.

Congenital megabladder is a type of autosomal dominant, physical, and bladder disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and also has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, congenital megabladder is characterized by a massively dilated urinary bladder with disruption of the smooth muscle in the wall of the bladder, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYOCD gene on chromosome 17p12. It is also exactly synonymous with MGBL.

Immunodeficiency 72 is a type of autosomal recessive and combined immunodeficiency, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a range of symptoms that manifest in the first year of life, including recurrent infections or systemic inflammation, increased susceptibility to bacterial and viral infections, development of atopy or allergies, hepatosplenomegaly, lymphoproliferation, and variable immune cell abnormalities. These symptoms are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NCKAP1L gene located on chromosome 12q13.1-q13.2. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 72 is exactly synonymous with immunodeficiency 72 with autoinflammation.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 2 (NSXLID2) is classified as a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, an X-linked dominant disease, and falls under conditions that have a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability in males, and mild intellectual disability in females. Additionally, affected males often present with relative short stature, a large head, a highly arched palate, square face, prominent ears, and large testicular volumes. The condition is caused by hemizygous or heterozygous mutations in a region on chromosome Xp22.3. NSXLID2 is also known by its exact synonyms MRX2 and X-linked mental retardation 2.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 73 (NSXLID73) is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also recognized as a type of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, NSXLID73 is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that exhibits mild to moderate intellectual disability in males due to a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xp22.2. Additionally, NSXLID73 is precisely referred to by its exact synonyms MRX73 and X-linked mental retardation 73.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 104 is classified as a type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability, an X Linked Recessive Disease, and something that inherently has a material basis in X Linked Recessive Inheritance. It is defined as a Non-Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disability characterized by a spectrum of symptoms including global developmental delay, mild to severe intellectual disability, variable seizures, poor or absent speech, and behavioral problems in males, all of which have a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the FRMPD4 gene located on chromosome Xp22.2. Furthermore, Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 104 is exactly synonymous with MRX104 and X-Linked Mental Retardation 104.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 19, also precisely known as MRX19 and X-linked mental retardation 19, is categorized as a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and falls under the broader classification of X-linked dominant diseases. This specific condition is an example of disorders that have a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability, with its material basis in hemizygous or heterozygous mutations in the RPS6KA3 gene located on chromosome Xp22.12.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 103 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and also falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability distinguished by intellectual disability and facial feature anomalies, which arises from a hemizygous mutation in the KLHL15 gene located on chromosome Xp22.11. Additionally, non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 103 is precisely known by two synonyms: MRX103 and X-linked mental retardation 103.

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:non_syndromic_x_linked_intellectual_disability_arx_related rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :x_linked_recessive_inheritance ],
        :non_syndromic_x_linked_intellectual_disability,
        :x_linked_recessive_disease ;
    :has_definition "A non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to profound intellectual disability with variable additional features that has_material_basis_in hemizygous mutation in ARX on chromosome Xp21.3." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "ARX-related intellectual disability",
        "MRXARX",
        "X-linked mental retardation 29",
        "X-linked mental retardation 29 and others",
        "X-linked mental retardation 32",
        "X-linked mental retardation 33",
        "X-linked mental retardation 38",
        "X-linked mental retardation 43",
        "X-linked mental retardation 52",
        "X-linked mental retardation 54",
        "X-linked mental retardation 76",
        "X-linked mental retardation 87",
        "X-linked mental retardation with or without seizures ARX-related" .
text:
Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability ARX related is a specific type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and is also classified as an X-linked recessive disease. This condition fundamentally involves a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability marked by moderate to profound intellectual disability, with variable additional features, which originates from a hemizygous mutation in the ARX gene located on chromosome Xp21.3.

This condition is alternatively known by several exact synonyms, including ARX-related intellectual disability, MRXARX, X-linked mental retardation 29 (with "and others" indicating additional unspecified synonyms), X-linked mental retardation 32, X-linked mental retardation 33, X-linked mental retardation 38, X-linked mental retardation 43, X-linked mental retardation 52, X-linked mental retardation 54, X-linked mental retardation 76, X-linked mental retardation 87, and X-linked mental retardation with or without seizures ARX-related.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 21 is a condition that falls under several categories and has multiple designations. Firstly, it is recognized as a type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability. Additionally, it is classified as a type of X Linked Recessive Disease and is characterized by its material basis in X Linked Recessive Inheritance. The condition is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is characterized by a range of cognitive neurologic impairments. These impairments vary from moderate mental retardation to high-functioning autism and are a result of a hemizygous mutation in the IL1RAPL1 gene located on chromosome Xp21.3-p21.2.

Furthermore, Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 21 is known by several exact synonyms, including MRX21, MRX34, X-Linked Mental Retardation 21, X-Linked Mental Retardation 21/34, and X-Linked Mental Retardation 34, illustrating its diverse nomenclature within the medical and research communities.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 20 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by a mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11-q21. It is also precisely known as MRX20 and X-linked mental retardation 20.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 58 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, a type of X-linked recessive disease, and a type that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability and no consistent dysmorphic features, which has its material basis in hemizygous mutation in the TSPAN7 gene on chromosome Xp11.4. Additionally, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 58 has the exact synonyms MRX58 and X-linked mental retardation 58.

Female Restricted Syndromic X-Linked Intellectual Disability 99 (FRSXID99) is classified as a type of Syndromic X-Linked Intellectual Disability, a type of X-Linked Dominant Disease, and a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of X-Linked Dominant Inheritance. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by delayed psychomotor development, mild to moderate intellectual disability, and a wide range of additional congenital anomalies, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in the USP9X gene located on chromosome Xp11.4. Furthermore, FRSXID99 is also known by its exact synonyms MRXS99F, X-Linked Female Restricted Facial Dysmorphism-Short Stature-Choanal Atresia-Intellectual Disability, and Female-Restricted Syndromic X-Linked Mental Retardation 99, indicating the various aspects and characteristics of this condition.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 99 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by developmental delay, hypotonia, and variable behavioral abnormalities that is caused by a hemizygous mutation in the USP9X gene on chromosome Xp11.4. Additionally, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 99 is exactly synonymous with MRX99 and X-linked mental retardation 99.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 14 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by moderate intellectual disability and impaired speech, with its material basis in a mutation located on chromosome Xp11.3-q13.3. This condition is precisely synonymous with MRX14 and X-linked mental retardation 14.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 45 is a specific type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that is characterized by nonprogressive intellectual disability during childhood, large and simple ears, relatively large hands, and normal behavior, with its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.3-p11.21. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with MRX45 and X-linked mental retardation 45.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 50 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, characterized by moderate intellectual disability that has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.3-p11.21. It is also exactly synonymous with MRX50, X-linked intellectual developmental disorder 50, X-linked mental retardation 50, and XLID50.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 84 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and is also categorized as a type of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by being a type of disorder that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by nonspecific intellectual disability, which has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.3-q22.3. Furthermore, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 84 is exactly synonymous with MRX84 and X-linked mental retardation 84.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 89, also known exactly as MRX89 and X-linked mental retardation 89, is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a form of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific type of X-linked dominant inheritance that fundamentally has a material basis. This particular disability is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability marked by severe developmental delay due to a heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.3.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 92 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability that has its material basis in hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.3. This condition is also known as MRX92 and X-linked mental retardation 92, which are its exact synonyms. Additionally, non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 92 is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 81 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, and it is also characterized as a type of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is associated with a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability that has a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xp11.2-q12. Furthermore, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 81 has the exact synonyms MRX81 and X-linked mental retardation 81.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 9, which is also exactly known as MRX44, MRX9, X-linked mental retardation 44, and X-linked mental retardation 9, is classified as a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, an X-linked recessive disease, and something that inherently has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. This particular disability is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by nonprogressive intellectual disability, which originates from a hemizygous mutation in the FTSJ1 gene located on chromosome Xp11.23.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 96 (NSXLID96) is a specific type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability, which also categorizes it as a type of X Linked Recessive Disease. It shares the characteristic of having a material basis in X Linked Recessive Inheritance. NSXLID96 is defined as a Non-Syndromic X-Linked Intellectual Disability that is characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability, which has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the SYP gene located on chromosome Xp11.23. Furthermore, NSXLID96 is precisely synonymous with MRX96 and X-Linked Mental Retardation 96.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 105 (NSXLID105) is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, also classified as an X-linked recessive disease. This condition is characterized by borderline to moderate intellectual disability, variable poor or absent speech, and behavioral problems, and it arises from a hemizygous mutation in the USP27X gene located on chromosome Xp11.23. Furthermore, NSXLID105 falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is precisely referred to by its exact synonyms, MRX105 and X-linked mental retardation 105.

Chromosome Xp11.22 duplication syndrome is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by moderate intellectual disability and slow speech development, with its material basis in the duplication of a small region within chromosome Xp11.22 involving both the HSD17B10 and HUWE1 genes. This condition is also exactly synonymous with MRX17, MRX31, X-linked mental retardation 17, X-linked mental retardation 31, and Xp11.22 microduplication syndrome.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 1 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, and it is also classified as a type of X-linked dominant disease. This condition is typified by its association with X-linked dominant inheritance, indicating that it fundamentally arises from specific genetic mechanisms. It is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability in males and varying levels of intellectual disability in females, which has its material basis in hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in the IQSEC2 gene on chromosome Xp11.22.

Additionally, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 1 is known by several exact synonyms, including MRX1, MRX18, MRX78, X-linked mental retardation 1, X-linked mental retardation 1/78, X-linked mental retardation 18, and X-linked mental retardation 78.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 77 (NSXLID77) is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, as well as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has its material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, NSXLID77 is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability, severe speech problems, and aggressive behavior, which has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation located in a region on chromosome Xq12-q21.3. Furthermore, NSXLID77 is also known by its exact synonyms MRX77 and X-linked mental retardation 77.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 100 (NSXLID100) is a type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability and is also classified as a type of X Linked Recessive Disease. It falls under diseases that at least have a material basis in some X Linked Recessive Inheritance. NSXLID100 is characterized by a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that ranges from mild to moderate and has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the KIF4A gene located on chromosome Xq13.1. It is exactly synonymous with MRX100 and X-linked mental retardation 100.

Non syndromic X linked intellectual disability 90 (NSXLID90) is a type of non syndromic X linked intellectual disability, which falls under the broader category of X linked recessive diseases. It is characterized specifically by a type of condition that has a material basis in some X linked recessive inheritance. The definition of NSXLID90 is particularly detailed as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability distinguished by moderate to severe intellectual disability that results from a hemizygous mutation in the DLG3 gene located on chromosome Xq13.1. Furthermore, NSXLID90 is precisely known by its exact synonyms MRX90 and X-linked mental retardation 90.

Tonne Kalscheuer syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also known by its exact synonyms MRX61, TOKAS, and X-linked mental retardation 61. Additionally, it is referred to as intellectual developmental disorder with or without hand and foot anomalies, genital anomalies, or congenital diaphragmatic hernia. This condition is characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, speech delay, and behavioral abnormalities in most patients. Moreover, it presents variable congenital anomalies in some patients. The syndrome has its material basis in a mutation in the RLIM gene located on chromosome Xq13.2.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 91 (NSXLID91) is classified as a form of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is a type of X-linked dominant disease. It specifically relates to conditions that inherently have a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. NSXLID91 is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe intellectual disability, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xq13.3. Furthermore, NSXLID91 is precisely referred to by two exact synonyms: MRX91 and X-linked mental retardation 91.

Non Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disability 98 is a type of Non Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disability, as well as a type of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. This disability is defined as a Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by delayed psychomotor development, poor speech, behavioral abnormalities, poor overall growth, dysmorphic facial features, and often early-onset seizures, with males generally more severely affected than females. It has a material basis in heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in NEXMIF on chromosome Xq13.3. Moreover, Non Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disability 98 is also known by its exact synonyms MRX98 and X-linked mental retardation 98.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 93 is classified as a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, and it falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, this disability is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability featuring mild to moderate intellectual impairment and macrocephaly, which is caused by a hemizygous mutation in the BRWD3 gene located on chromosome Xq21.1. Additionally, Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 93 is also known by its exact synonyms: MRX93, X-linked mental retardation 93, and X-linked mental retardation with macrocephaly.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 97 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by a mild to moderate intellectual disability with speech delay, which has a material basis in mutation in the ZNF711 gene on chromosome Xq21.1. This condition is also exactly known as MRX65, MRX97, MRXZ, X-linked mental retardation 65, and X-linked mental retardation 97.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 53 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and also falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a condition that has its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, specifically through a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xq22.2-q26. This particular condition is precisely referred to as MRX53 and X-linked mental retardation 53.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 101 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It also represents a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. This particular disorder is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay, which is caused by a hemizygous mutation in the MID2 gene located on chromosome Xq22.3. Additionally, non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 101 is exactly synonymous with MRX101 and X-linked mental retardation 101.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 23 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by decreased verbal but not performance IQs, which has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xq23-q24. It is also exactly synonymous with MRX23 and X-linked mental retardation 23.

Non syndromic X linked intellectual disability 63 is a type of non syndromic X linked intellectual disability, which is also categorized as a type of X linked dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in X linked dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability marked by moderate to severe nonprogressive intellectual disability in males and moderate intellectual disability to normal intelligence in females, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the ACSL4 gene on chromosome Xq23. Additionally, non syndromic X linked intellectual disability 63 is known by several exact synonyms including ACSL4-related intellectual disability, MRX63, MRX68, X-linked mental retardation 63, and X-linked mental retardation 68.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 30 (NSXLID30) is categorized as a type of both Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability and X Linked Recessive Disease. It is recognized for having a material basis in X Linked Recessive Inheritance. NSXLID30 is specifically defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability, which is attributed to a hemizygous mutation in the PAK3 gene located on chromosome Xq23. Furthermore, NSXLID30 is known by several exact synonyms including MRX30, MRX47, X-linked mental retardation 30, X-linked mental retardation 30/47, and X-linked mental retardation 47.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 82 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific form that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This particular disability is defined by a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xq24-q25. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with MRX82 and X-linked mental retardation 82.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 88 is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate to severe intellectual disability, which has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xq24. It is also precisely known by the synonyms MRX88 and X-linked mental retardation 88.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 107 (NSXLID107) is a specific type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which also falls under the category of X-linked dominant diseases. This condition is characterized by a type of inheritance that has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. NSXLID107 is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that ranges from mild to moderate in severity and has its material basis in heterozygous or hemizygous mutations in the CXorf56 gene located on chromosome Xq24. Additionally, NSXLID107 is precisely synonymous with MRX107 and X-linked mental retardation 107.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 46, also exactly known as MRX46 and X-linked mental retardation 46, is a type of non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by moderate intellectual disability in most patients, which has a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in a region on chromosome Xq25-q26.

X-linked intellectual disability short stature overweight syndrome is a syndromic form of X-linked intellectual disability and falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. This particular syndrome is defined by a condition that has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, specifically through a hemizygous mutation in the THOC2 gene located on chromosome Xq25. It is characterized by a spectrum of symptoms ranging from borderline to severe intellectual disability, often accompanied by speech delay, short stature, elevated body mass index, and a pattern of truncal obesity in older males. Additionally, this syndrome is synonymously known as MRX12, MRX35, X-linked mental retardation 12, and X-linked mental retardation 35.

Non syndromic X linked intellectual disability 42 is a type of non syndromic X linked intellectual disability, characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability that has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xq26. It is also exactly synonymous with MRX42 and X-linked mental retardation 42.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 41 is a type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability and falls under the category of X Linked Dominant Disease. It is characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDI1 gene on chromosome Xq28. This condition is precisely known by several exact synonyms including MRX41, MRX48, X-linked Mental Retardation 41, and X-linked Mental Retardation 48.

Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability 72 (NSXLID72) is classified as a type of Non Syndromic X Linked Intellectual Disability, X Linked Recessive Disease, and is regarded as a condition that inherently has a material basis in X Linked Recessive Inheritance. It is precisely defined as a Non-Syndromic X-Linked Intellectual Disability that manifests due to a hemizygous mutation in the RAB39B gene located on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, NSXLID72 is exactly synonymous with MRX72 and X-Linked Mental Retardation 72.

Raynaud Claes syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which also falls under the category of X-linked dominant diseases. This condition is characterized by a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. Specifically, Raynaud Claes syndrome is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability marked by a range from borderline to severe intellectual disability, impaired language development, and variable additional features. These features include behavioral problems, psychiatric disorders, seizures, progressive ataxia, brain abnormalities, and facial dysmorphisms. The syndrome has its material basis in heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in the CLCN4 gene located on chromosome Xp22.2. Furthermore, Raynaud Claes syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including MRX15, MRX49, MRXSRC, X-linked mental retardation 15, and X-linked mental retardation 49.

Immunodeficiency 73b with defective neutrophil chemotaxis and lymphopenia, also known exactly as IMD73B, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and a type of combined immunodeficiency. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of immunodeficiency 73b encompasses a combined immunodeficiency that is marked by the onset of recurrent infections in infancy or early childhood, along with various immune system abnormalities. These abnormalities include B- and T-cell lymphopenia, reduced immunoglobulin subsets, decreased TCR excision circles, dysfunctional T cells, reduced NK cells, neutropenia, and impaired neutrophil chemotaxis. This disease specifically has its material basis in a heterozygous gain-of-function mutation in the RAC2 gene located on chromosome 22q13.1.

Immunodeficiency 73c, characterized by defective neutrophil chemotaxis and hypogammaglobulinemia, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a combined immunodeficiency. It is defined as a combined immunodeficiency that manifests through recurrent infections beginning in early childhood, impaired neutrophil chemotaxis, decreased B cells, hypogammaglobulinemia, and other variable features, all of which have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RAC2 gene located on chromosome 22q12. Additionally, Immunodeficiency 73c with these characteristics is also known by its exact synonym, IMD73C, and is recognized as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

X-linked immunodeficiency 74 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, which is also a form of T cell deficiency and is characterized by a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a T cell deficiency characterized by severe respiratory insufficiency in response to infection with the COVID-19 coronavirus and impaired signaling through the TLR7 pathway, which is due to a hemizygous mutation in the TLR7 gene on chromosome Xp22.2. Furthermore, X-linked immunodeficiency 74 is known by several exact synonyms, including IMD74, TLR7 deficiency, X-linked immunodeficiency 74, COVID-19-related, and respiratory insufficiency due to SARS-CoV-2 viral infection.

Immunodeficiency 73a with defective neutrophil chemotaxis and leukocytosis, also known exactly as IMD73A or neutrophil immunodeficiency syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of combined immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by recurrent infections starting in early infancy, leukocytosis, neutrophilia, decreased TCR excision circles, impaired neutrophil chemotaxis, and T-cell abnormalities. It has its material basis in a heterozygous loss of function mutation in the RAC2 gene located on chromosome 22q13.1. This disease is part of a broader category that encompasses any condition having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency is a type of mitochondrial complex I deficiency and is defined as a mitochondrial complex I deficiency that has its material basis in mutation in a gene in the nuclear genome. Moreover, it has the exact synonym MC1DN.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency 6 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NDUFS2 gene located on chromosome 1q23. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with MC1DN6.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency 25 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency that has its material basis in homozygous and compound heterozygous mutations in the NDUFB3 gene on chromosome 2q33.1. Additionally, it has the exact synonym MC1DN25.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency 5, which is exactly synonymous with MC1DN5, is a form of autosomal recessive disease and a specific type of nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NDUFS1 gene located on chromosome 2q33.3.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency 22 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiencies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NDUFA10 gene located on chromosome 2q37.3. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with MC1DN22.

Nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiency 18 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of nuclear type mitochondrial complex I deficiencies. Retinitis pigmentosa 86, which has the exact synonym RP86, is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a specific form of retinitis pigmentosa. This condition is characterized by night blindness followed by a progressive narrowing of visual fields and a decline in visual acuity, which has its material basis in a mutation in the KIAA1549 gene on chromosome 7q34. Furthermore, retinitis pigmentosa 86 is considered to be an instance of something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance.

Retinitis pigmentosa 87 (RP87), which also has the exact synonym "retinitis pigmentosa 87 with choroidal involvement," is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of retinitis pigmentosa. This condition is characterized as being part of diseases that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. RP87 is defined by a slowly progressive visual disturbance and extensive choroid/retinal atrophy, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the RPE65 gene located on chromosome 1p31.3.

Retinitis Pigmentosa 88 (RP88) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of Retinitis Pigmentosa. It is described by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of Retinitis Pigmentosa 88 includes characteristics such as night blindness and constriction of peripheral visual fields, with mildly reduced visual acuity, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RP1L1 gene located on chromosome 8p23.1.

Retinitis pigmentosa 89 (RP89) is a type of retinitis pigmentosa and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the onset of retinitis pigmentosa in the first decade of life and additional features of ciliopathy, stemming from a heterozygous mutation in the KIF3B gene on chromosome 20q11.21. This condition is also understood as a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Retinitis pigmentosa 90, which is exactly synonymous with RP90, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of retinitis pigmentosa. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of retinitis pigmentosa 90 includes it being a retinitis pigmentosa that is characterized by the onset in the first decade of life of night blindness, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IDH3A gene on chromosome 15q25.1.

Uruguay faciocardiomusculoskeletal syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by a distinctive facial appearance, muscular hypertrophy, and cardiac ventricular hypertrophy. This syndrome occurs due to a hemizygous mutation in the FHL1 gene on chromosome Xq26.3. It is also precisely known as FCMSU.

Terminal osseous dysplasia is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by a condition that, at a minimum, has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome marked by skeletal dysplasia of the limbs, pigmentary defects of the skin, and recurrent digital fibroma during infancy, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the FLNA gene located on chromosome Xq28. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including ODPD, ODPF syndrome, TOD, TODPD, digital osseous dysplasia with facial pigmentary defects and multiple frenula, and terminal osseous dysplasia-pigmentary defects syndrome.

X-linked spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia is a type of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia and a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia that has a material basis in a hemizygous mutation in BGN on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, X-linked spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia has exact synonyms SEMD X-linked and SEMDX.

Corpus Callosum Agenesis Abnormal Genitalia Syndrome is a type of syndrome which falls under the category of X-linked monogenic diseases, and it is something that has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance as well as a phenotype that includes spasticity. This syndrome is characterized by the agenesis of the corpus callosum, severe intellectual disability, seizures, and spasticity, with males exhibiting a severe phenotype and females showing a mild or non-affected phenotype. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the ARX gene on chromosome Xp21.3. Corpus Callosum Agenesis Abnormal Genitalia Syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including ACC with abnormal genitalia, Proud syndrome, Proud-Levine-Carpenter syndrome, corpus callosum agenesis with abnormal genitalia, and microcephaly-corpus callosum agenesis-abnormal genitalia syndrome.

Chime syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by colobomas, congenital heart defects, migratory ichthyosiform dermatosis, intellectual disability, and ear anomalies. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PIGL gene on chromosome 17p11.2. Chime syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including PIGL-CDG, Zunich neuroectodermal syndrome, Zunich-Kaye syndrome, coloboma-congenital heart disease-ichthyosiform dermatosis-intellectual disability-ear anomalies syndrome, congenital disorder of glycosylation due to PIGL deficiency, neuroectodermal dysplasia, CHIME type, and neuroectodermal syndrome, Zunich type.
