Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 20 (HLD20) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the progressive loss of developmental milestones starting at about 12 to 16 months of age after normal early development. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in CNP on chromosome 17q21.2. Additionally, hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 20 is a type related to conditions that at least have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Inflammatory Bowel Disease 30 (IBD30) is a type of inflammatory bowel disease that is also categorized under autosomal dominant diseases, indicating its genetic inheritance pattern where it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as an inflammatory bowel disease characterized by symptoms such as abdominal pain and watery or bloody diarrhea, with changes in the intestinal tract consistent with Crohn's disease. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CARD8 gene on chromosome 19q13.33. Additionally, IBD30 is exactly synonymous with "Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn Disease) 30".

Inflammatory bowel disease 29 (IBD29) is a type of inflammatory bowel disease and an autosomal dominant disease, which essentially means it has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, IBD29 is defined by an inflammatory bowel disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the INAVA gene located on chromosome 1q32.1. Furthermore, IBD29 is exactly synonymous with IBD29.

X-linked dyserythropoietic anemia is a type of anemia that is classified as an X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific kind of anemia that has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, this anemia is defined by early-onset anemia and bone marrow erythroid hypoplasia with variable neutropenia due to a hemizygous splice-site mutation in the GATA1 gene on chromosome Xp11.23. This mutation impairs the expression of the long isoform of GATA1, although the expression of a short form is observed. Furthermore, X-linked dyserythropoietic anemia is also known by its exact synonyms, "X-linked anemia with/without neutropenia and/or platelet abnormalities" and "X-linked dyserythropoietic anemia with abnormal platelets and neutropenia."

X-linked atrophic macular degeneration is a type of macular degeneration and also a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by macular atrophy that leads to progressive loss of visual acuity with minimal peripheral visual impairment, which has a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the RPGR gene located on chromosome Xp11.4. Additionally, X-linked atrophic macular degeneration is described as having a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance.

De Sanctis Cacchione syndrome is a type of Xeroderma Pigmentosum characterized by Xeroderma Pigmentosum, short stature, intellectual disabilities, and progressive neurologic degeneration. It also has an exact synonym, which is Xeroderma Pigmentosum with neurologic manifestation.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 78 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness, which has an exact synonym DFNA78. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness characterized by congenital onset of profound bilateral sensorineural hearing loss affecting all frequencies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the carboxy-terminal domain of the SLC12A2 gene on chromosome 5q23.3.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 79 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness, which has an exact synonym DFNA79. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCD5 gene on chromosome 4q21.22.

Noonan Syndrome 13 (NS13) is a type of Noonan Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is defined by a specific set of characteristics. These characteristics include developmental delay, variably impaired intellectual development, reduced postnatal growth, and craniofacial anomalies. The condition's material basis is a heterozygous mutation in the MAPK1 gene located on chromosome 22q11.22. This mutation enhances the phosphorylation of the kinase. Moreover, Noonan Syndrome 13 has an exact synonym, NS13, and is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 116 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which is defined as an autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CLDN9 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with DFNB116.

Spermatogenic failure 45, which has the exact synonym SPGF45, is a specific type of spermatogenic failure that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by male infertility owing to severe teratozoospermia, featuring multiple morphological abnormalities of the flagella, and disruption of the axonemal complex and mitochondrial sheath. This condition fundamentally arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DNAH2 gene located on chromosome 17p13.1. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 45 is recognized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic Failure 46, which has the exact synonym SPGF46, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure. It is characterized by being a spermatogenic failure that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a spermatogenic failure that results in male infertility due to asthenoteratozoospermia with multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella and disorganization of the axonemal and periaxonemal structures. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DNAH8 gene on chromosome 6p21.2.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 74 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness and has an exact synonym, DFNA74. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PDE1C gene on chromosome 7p14.3.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 75 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness and has an exact synonym, DFNA75. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRRAP gene on chromosome 7q22.1.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 76 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness and has the exact synonym DFNA76. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive or nonprogressive hearing loss with variable age at onset, which typically is more severe at higher frequencies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PLS1 gene on chromosome 3q23.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 77 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness and has the exact synonym DFNA77. It is defined as an autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ABCC1 gene on chromosome 16p13.11.

Noonan syndrome 11 is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is a subset of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan syndrome characterized by the clinical characteristics of Noonan syndrome, varying impairment of intellectual development, and cardiac hypertrophy, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MRAS gene on chromosome 3q22.3. Additionally, Noonan syndrome 11 has the exact synonym NS11.

Noonan syndrome 12 is a type of Noonan syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Noonan syndrome characterized by macrocephaly, facial anomalies including hypertelorism, downslanting palpebral fissures, and low-set ears, alongside other Noonan syndrome features, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RRAS2 gene on chromosome 11p15.2. Additionally, Noonan syndrome 12 has an exact synonym, NS12.

Wrinkly Skin Syndrome (WSS) is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which essentially means it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by sagging or wrinkly skin, reduced skin elasticity, delayed closure of the fontanel, typically mild developmental delay, and variable other skeletal, neurological, and facial features. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATP6V0A2 gene on chromosome 12q24.31.

Hereditary combined deficiency of vitamin K dependent clotting factors (VKCFD), also known as hereditary combined deficiency of factors II, VII, IX, and X, is characterized as both a type of monogenic disease and a blood coagulation disease. This condition is defined as a blood coagulation disease that is marked by reduced hepatic gamma-carboxylation of glutamic acid residues of all vitamin K-dependent blood coagulation factors, including the anticoagulant factors protein C and protein S. This results in a bleeding tendency that is typically reversible with the oral administration of vitamin K. The basis of this disease is a heritable mutation, aligning it with conditions that have their foundation in genetic abnormalities.

Combined deficiency of vitamin K dependent clotting factors 1 (VKCFD1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a hereditary combined deficiency of vitamin K dependent clotting factors. This condition is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. VKCFD1 is defined as a hereditary combined deficiency of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GGCX gene on chromosome 2p11.2.

Combined deficiency of vitamin K dependent clotting factors 2 (VKCFD2) is a type of hereditary combined deficiency of vitamin K dependent clotting factors, classified as an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a hereditary combined deficiency that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VKORC1 gene located on chromosome 16p11.2. Additionally, it is recognized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic Failure 47 (SPGF47) is an autosomal recessive disease and a type of spermatogenic failure, which is explicitly characterized by a condition that includes asthenoteratospermia, reduced sperm concentrations, and immotile spermatozoa with short or absent flagella, alongside centriolar abnormalities. This condition is grounded in material basis through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DZIP1 gene located on chromosome 13q32.1. Additionally, it falls under the category of disorders that have at least some autosomal recessive inheritance as their material basis.

Spermatogenic failure 48 is a type of spermatogenic failure and is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It also falls into the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific spermatogenic failure, also known exactly as SPGF48, is defined as a condition characterized by impaired spermatogenesis, particularly occurring at meiosis, and it has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the M1AP gene located on chromosome 2p13.1.

Mayer Rokitansky Kuster Hauser syndrome is a type of syndrome defined as a condition characterized by the aplasia of the uterus and the upper part of the vagina in patients who have normal secondary sex characteristics and a 46,XX karyotype. This syndrome is also exactly synonymous with MRKH syndrome and Rokitansky syndrome.

Mayer-Rokitansky-Kuster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome type 1 is a type of Mayer-Rokitansky-Kuster-Hauser syndrome. It is characterized by isolated utero-vaginal atresia in patients who have a normal 46 XX karyotype. This syndrome is also precisely known by its exact synonyms: MRKH syndrome type 1, Rokitansky sequence, and congenital absence of uterus and vagina.

Mayer Rokitansky Kuster Hauser Syndrome Type 2 is a specific type of Mayer Rokitansky Kuster Hauser Syndrome. It is defined as a Mayer-Rokitansky-Kuster-Hauser syndrome characterized by congenital aplasia of the uterus and upper two thirds of the vagina that is associated with at least one other malformation such as renal, vertebral, or, less commonly, auditory and cardiac defects. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: MRKH Syndrome Type 2, MURCS, MURCS association, atypical MRKH syndrome, mullerian duct aplasia, unilateral renal aplasia, and cervicothoracic somite dysplasia, and mullerian duct aplasia-renal dysplasia-cervical somite anomalies syndrome.

Urocanase deficiency is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a histidine metabolism disease, and a condition that inherently involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a histidine metabolism disease characterized by the presence of urocanic aciduria alongside variable manifestations that may include intellectual disability and intermittent ataxia. This condition is caused by either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the UROC1 gene located on chromosome 3q21.3. Urocanase deficiency is identified by several exact synonyms, including UROCD, encephalopathy due to urocanase deficiency, high urine urocanic acid levels, urocanate hydratase deficiency, and urocanic aciduria.

Schinzel type phocomelia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by severe malformations of upper and lower limbs, a severely hypoplastic pelvis, and abnormal genitalia, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WNT7A gene on chromosome 3p25.1. Schinzel type phocomelia has several exact synonyms, including AARRS, Al Awadi-Raas-Rothschild syndrome, Al-Awadi/Raas-Rothschild/Schinzel phocomelia syndrome, LPHAS, Schinzel phocomelia syndrome, absence of ulna and fibula with severe limb deficiency, aplasia/hypoplasia of limbs and pelvis, congenital absence of ulna and fibula, limb/pelvis-hypoplasia/aplasia syndrome, and severe limb deficit.

Mismatch repair cancer syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a predisposition for the development of a broad spectrum of malignancies during childhood, including mainly brain, hematological, and gastrointestinal cancers. This syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the mismatch repair genes MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, or PMS2 on chromosomes 3p22.2, 2p21-p16, 2p16.3, and 7p22.1, respectively. Mismatch repair cancer syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including BTP1 syndrome, BTPS1, CMMR-D syndrome, CMMRDS, MMR deficiency, Turcot syndrome, brain tumor-polyposis syndrome 1, childhood cancer syndrome, and constitutional mismatch repair deficiency syndrome.

Familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis is a type of congenital hypothyroidism, defined as a congenital hypothyroidism characterized by a deficiency in thyroid hormone that is present from birth and results from defects in thyroid hormone synthesis.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, and it is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DUOXA2 gene located on chromosome 15q21.1. Additionally, thyroid dyshormonogenesis 5 is exactly synonymous with TDH5 and also known as genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 5.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in SLC5A5 on chromosome 19p13.11. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including TDH1, genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 1, and iodide accumulation, transport, or trapping defect.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 2a is a specific type of familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, which is an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, also known as TDH2A, genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 2A, iodide peroxidase deficiency, or thyroid peroxidase deficiency, is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TPO gene located on chromosome 2p25.3.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 3, which has the exact synonyms TDH3 and genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in TG on chromosome 8q24.22.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IYD gene on chromosome 6q25.1. Additionally, thyroid dyshormonogenesis 4 is exactly synonymous with TDH4, deiodinase deficiency, genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 4, and iodotyrosine dehalogenase deficiency.

Thyroid dyshormonogenesis 6 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial thyroid dyshormonogenesis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in DUOX2 on chromosome 15q21.1. Furthermore, thyroid dyshormonogenesis 6 is exactly synonymous with TDH6 and genetic defect in thyroid hormonogenesis 6.

Distal arthrogryposis type 1c (DA1C) is a subtype of distal arthrogryposis type 1, which is an autosomal genetic disease. It specifically falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. DA1C is characterized by congenital contractures, scoliosis, and short stature, which arise from either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the MYLPF gene located on chromosome 16p11.2.

Tetraamelia syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by rudimentary or absent appendages and anomalies involving the cranium and face, urogenital system, anorectum, heart, lungs, skeleton, and/or central nervous system. It has exact synonyms including TETAMS, tetra-amelia syndrome, and tetraamelia-multiple malformations syndrome.

Tetraamelia syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a subtype of tetraamelia syndrome, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by complete limb agenesis without defects of scapulae or clavicles, and this condition is specifically caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WNT3 gene located on chromosome 17q21.31-q21.32. Additionally, Tetraamelia syndrome 1 is exactly synonymous with TETAMS1 and tetra-amelia syndrome 1.

Tetraamelia syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of tetraamelia syndrome that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by rudimentary or absent appendages, bilateral agenesis of the lungs, pulmonary vascular abnormalities, and dysmorphic features, with this condition resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in RSPO2 on chromosome 8q23.1. Tetraamelia syndrome 2 is also exactly synonymized as TETAMS2, tetra-amelia with pulmonary hypoplasia, and tetraamelia with pulmonary hypoplasia, highlighting its defining features.

Filippi syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that originates from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by short stature, microcephaly, syndactyly, intellectual disability, pre- and postnatal growth failure, and facial dysmorphism, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CKAP2L gene on chromosome 2q14.1. Additionally, Filippi syndrome is exactly synonymous with Scott craniodigital syndrome with mental retardation and is also known as type 1 syndactyly-microcephaly-intellectual disability syndrome.

Spondyloperipheral dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by platyspondyly, brachydactyly type E changes, bilateral short ulnae, and mild short stature due to a heterozygous mutation in the COL2A1 gene on chromosome 12q13.11. Additionally, spondyloperipheral dysplasia is also known by its exact synonym, spondyloperipheral dysplasia-short ulna syndrome.

Spondylometaepiphyseal dysplasia short limb hand type is a form of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by short stature, short limbs and hands, and distinct radiological features including platyspondyly, metaphyseal, and epiphyseal involvement, short tubular bones of the limbs, and abnormal calcification of cartilage. This condition stems from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DDR2 gene located on chromosome 1q23.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms: SMED short limb-abnormal calcification type, SMED short limb-hand type, SMED type 2, SMED, type II, SMED-SL, SMED-SL/AC, and spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia-short limb-abnormal calcification syndrome, indicating its varied but specific classification within spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasias and highlighting its genetic basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity is a type of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia and is also considered a disease that affects some ligaments of the vertebral column. It is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia characterized by spinal abnormalities and gross articular hypermobility. Additionally, it has the exact synonym SEMDJL.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity type 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it also falls under the broader category of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity. This condition is specifically associated with autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity characterized by vertebral abnormalities and ligamentous laxity leading to spinal misalignment, progressive severe kyphoscoliosis, thoracic asymmetry, and respiratory compromise. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the B3GALT6 gene on chromosome 1p36.33. Additionally, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity type 1 is exactly synonymous with SEMDJL1, and the full description also includes "with or without fractures" as part of its synonym, indicating the variability in its presentation.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity type 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the broader category of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity. It is characterized by a type of disorder that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The condition is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity characterized by features such as short stature, distinctive midface retrusion, progressive knee malalignment, generalized ligamentous laxity, multiple joint dislocations, and mild spinal deformity, all of which have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KIF22 gene on chromosome 16p11.2. Moreover, this condition is known by several exact synonyms: SEMD-MD, SEMDJL2, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxicity, Hall type, spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity, leptodactylic type, and spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with multiple dislocations, Hall type.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity type 3, also exactly known as SEMDJL3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia with joint laxity. This condition is characterized by various symptoms including multiple joint dislocations at birth, severe joint laxity, scoliosis, gracile metacarpals and metatarsals, delayed bone age, and poorly ossified carpal and tarsal bones. The material basis for this disease lies in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EXOC6B gene located on chromosome 2p13.2, which also underscores its classification as a disorder with autosomal recessive inheritance.

Osteogenesis imperfecta type 21 (OI21), also known exactly as osteogenesis imperfecta type XXI, is a specific form of osteogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by multiple fractures often resulting from minor trauma, disproportionate short stature, and scoliosis, all of which have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KDELR2 gene located on chromosome 7p22.1. This type of osteogenesis imperfecta is a manifestation of conditions that have at least a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy is a type of electroclinical syndrome and is defined as an electroclinical syndrome characterized by epileptiform activity and at least one other pathology that together contribute to cognitive and behavioral impairments, including developmental delay or regression, with onset anywhere from birth to adulthood.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 67 (DEE67), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 67, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is specifically noted for its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE67 is characterized by its onset in the first months of life, presenting with seizures, global developmental delay, impaired motor and intellectual development, poor or absent speech, movement disorders, and stereotypic or autistic behavior. The genetic underpinning of this disorder is a heterozygous mutation in the CUX2 gene located on chromosome 12q24.11-q24.12.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 68 (DEE68), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 68, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy. It is characterized by a progressive development of seizures starting in infancy, developmental delay, axial hypotonia, spasticity of the limbs, clonus, and cortical atrophy. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TRAK1 gene located on chromosome 3p22.1, indicating its autosomal recessive inheritance nature.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 69 (DEE69), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 69, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by a particular type that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE69 is a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy defined by early-onset refractory seizures, hypotonia, and profoundly impaired development, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1E gene located on chromosome 1q25.3.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 70 (DEE70), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 70, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a specific type of condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE70 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy with onset in the first months of life, featuring epileptic spasms or seizures, hypsarrhythmia on EEG, severely delayed psychomotor development including impaired or absent walking and language skills, and moderate to severe intellectual impairment. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PHACTR1 gene located on chromosome 6p24.1.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 71 (DEE71), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 71 and Glutaminase Deficiency with Neonatal Epileptic Encephalopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically classified under developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by a definition that includes early neonatal refractory seizures, respiratory failure, structural brain abnormalities, and cerebral edema, leading to death within weeks after birth. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GLS gene located on chromosome 2q32.2.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 72 (DEE72), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 72, is categorized under autosomal dominant diseases and is a specific type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The disorder is defined by its onset around 5 months of age, involving infantile spasms, hypsarrhythmia as observed on EEG, and severely delayed psychomotor development, which notably includes impaired or absent walking and language skills. This condition is attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the NEUROD2 gene located on chromosome 17q12.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 73 (DEE73), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 73, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a specific material basis rooted in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE73 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that presents within the first few months of life with refractory seizures, profound developmental delay, failure to thrive, hypotonia, and difficulties in walking, speaking, or feeding properly. This condition is due to a heterozygous mutation in the RNF13 gene located on chromosome 3q25.1.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 74 (DEE74), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 74, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a subset of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is defined by its nature of having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE74 is characterized by the onset in the first months of life of refractory seizures and severe global developmental delay accompanied by hypotonia, severe motor impairment, roving eye movements, and absent language. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GABRG2 gene on chromosome 5q34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 75 (DEE75), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 75, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is specifically associated with homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PARS2 gene on chromosome 1p32.3. The disease is defined by the onset in the first months of life of severe refractory seizures, multifocal spikes, and hypsarrhythmia observed on an EEG. Additionally, it is marked by severely impaired intellectual development, inability to walk, absence of speech, and hypotonia with axial hyperreflexia.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 76 (DEE76), also known as DECAM, developmental delay, epileptic encephalopathy, cerebral atrophy, and abnormal myelination, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 76, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by early-onset, usually refractory seizures, severely delayed global development, hypotonia, peripheral spasticity, and abnormalities on brain imaging, which originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ACTL6B gene on chromosome 7q22.1. This condition is also defined as something that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome 4 (MCAHS4) is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader classification of multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome and is a type of condition that has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. MCAHS4 is defined as a multiple congenital anomalies-hypotonia-seizures syndrome characterized by the onset in the first months of life of refractory seizures and severe global developmental delay. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PIGQ gene on chromosome 16p13.3. Furthermore, MCAHS4 is synonymously known as DEE77, GPIBD19, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 77, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 77, and glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 19.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 78 (DEE78), also known exactly as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 78, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically classified under developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is described as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE78 is defined by the onset in the first days or weeks of life of refractory seizures followed by severely impaired intellectual development, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the GABRA2 gene located on chromosome 4p12.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 79 (DEE79), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 79, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by its onset in the first months of life, featuring refractory seizures, severely impaired psychomotor development, hypomyelination, cerebral atrophy, and thinning of the corpus callosum. The material basis for DEE79 is a heterozygous mutation in the GABRA5 gene located on chromosome 15q12, which is associated with some autosomal dominant inheritance patterns.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 80 (DEE80), also known as GPIBD20, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 80, and glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 20, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by an onset in the first year of life of refractory seizures, severe global developmental delay, and defective synthesis of glycosylphosphatidylinositol. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PIGB gene on chromosome 15q21.3, aligning it as a disorder rooted in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 81 (DEE81), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 81, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by severe refractory seizures, little developmental progress, cerebral atrophy, impaired myelination, a thin corpus callosum, and progressive leukoencephalopathy. The material basis for DEE81 is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DMXL2 gene on chromosome 15q21.2, indicating that it indeed has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 83 (DEE83), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 83, is classified as a type of Autosomal Recessive Disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This particular condition is characterized by the onset in the first days or months of life of frequent, usually refractory, seizures and profoundly impaired development. The material basis for DEE83 is attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UGP2 gene located on chromosome 2p15.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 84 (DEE84), also known as Jamuar Syndrome or Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 84, is classified as a type of Autosomal Recessive Disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is specifically characterized by its onset in the first months or years of life, during which affected individuals experience refractory seizures, severely impaired global development, impaired intellectual development, absent speech, and an inability to walk. The material basis for DEE84 is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the UGDH gene located on chromosome 4p14, indicating its genetic foundation in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 86 (DEE86), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 86, is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically falling under the broader classification of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This classification is based on the condition's material basis, which stems from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined by its origin from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DALRD2 gene located on chromosome 3p21.31.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 87 (DEE87), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 87, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by global developmental delay, severely impaired motor and cognitive development, hypotonia, and the onset of frequent refractory seizures or infantile spasms between 6 and 15 months of age. It has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically in a heterozygous mutation in the CDK19 gene on chromosome 6q21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 88 (DEE88), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 88, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MDH1 gene located on chromosome 2p15.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 89 (DEE89), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 89, is categorized as a type of Autosomal Recessive Disease and falls under the broader classification of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This specific disorder is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by the onset in the first days or months of life of seizures, profound global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development, absent speech, axial hypotonia, and spastic quadriparesis. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GAD1 gene on chromosome 2q31.1.

Chondrodysplasia with joint dislocations GPAPP type is a type of autosomal recessive disease and osteochondrodysplasia. It is characterized by a specific condition that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. This disease, also known as GPAPP deficiency, is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia with a prenatal onset that includes a range of symptoms such as disproportionate short stature, limb shortening, joint hyperlaxity and/or dislocations, micrognathia, cleft palate, brachydactyly, short metacarpals, the presence of supernumerary carpal ossification centers, and dysmorphic facial features. These manifestations have their material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IMPAD1 gene located on chromosome 8q12.

BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia B is a type of autosomal recessive disease, tetrahydrobiopterin BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by hyperphenylalaninemia, depletion of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin, and progressive cognitive and motor deficits. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GCH1 gene on chromosome 14q22.2. BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia B is also known by its exact synonyms: GTP cyclohydrolase 1 deficiency, HPABH4B, and tetrahydrobiopterin-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia B.

Bosch Boonstra Schaaf optic atrophy syndrome (BBSOAS), also known precisely as optic atrophy-intellectual disability syndrome, is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. This syndrome is essentially characterized by delayed development, moderate intellectual disability, and optic atrophy, which has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NR2F1 gene located on chromosome 5q15. It is recognized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Tubulinopathy is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a congenital nervous system abnormality. It is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal inheritance. Tubulinopathy is defined as a congenital nervous system abnormality characterized by complex cortical malformations, including in most cases dysmorphic basal ganglia, that has its material basis in mutations in one or more of the tubulin genes.

Lissencephaly 9 with complex brainstem malformation, also known exactly as LIS9 and posterior-predominant lissencephaly-broad flat pons and medulla-midline crossing defects syndrome, is a type of lissencephaly and autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is a lissencephaly characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with poor or absent speech, pachygyria, lissencephaly, and malformation of the brainstem that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MACF1 gene on chromosome 1p34.3.

Lissencephaly 10, which has the exact synonym LIS10, is a type of lissencephaly and also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is considered a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Lissencephaly 10 is defined by a variety of symptoms including variably delayed development, mildly to moderately impaired intellectual development and language delay, seizures, and brain features consistent with neuronal migration defects, all of which are due to a heterozygous mutation in the CEP85L gene located on chromosome 6q22.31.

Lissencephaly 5, which is exactly synonymous with LIS5, is a type of lissencephaly and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It shares characteristics that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Lissencephaly 5 is defined as a lissencephaly characterized by hydrocephalus, seizures, severely delayed psychomotor development, and cobblestone changes in the cortex, which are more severe in the posterior region, along with subcortical band heterotopia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LAMB1 gene on chromosome 7q31.1.

Lissencephaly 7 with cerebellar hypoplasia, also exactly known as LIS7, is a type of lissencephaly and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific type of lissencephaly is defined by the absence of psychomotor development, facial dysmorphism, arthrogryposis, and early-onset intractable seizures leading to death in infancy. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDK5 gene located on chromosome 7q36.1.

Lissencephaly 3, also precisely known as LIS3, is identified as a type of lissencephaly and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized by a set of conditions including brain malformations, microcephaly, developmental delay, and epilepsy, all of which have their material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TUBA1A gene located on chromosome 12q13.12. Additionally, lissencephaly 3 is considered a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Lissencephaly 8 is a type of lissencephaly and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a lissencephaly characterized by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability with poor or absent speech, early-onset refractory seizures, and hypotonia, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMTC3 gene on chromosome 12q21.32. Lissencephaly 8 also has the exact synonym LIS8.
Microlissencephaly is a type of lissencephaly that is defined as a lissencephaly characterized by the combination of lissencephaly with severe congenital microcephaly.

Lissencephaly 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, microlissencephaly, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by lissencephaly, severe brain atrophy, extreme microcephaly, and profound intellectual disability that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NDE1 gene on chromosome 16p13.11. Furthermore, Lissencephaly 4 has the exact synonyms LIS4 and lissencephaly 4 with microcephaly.

Lissencephaly 6, which is exactly synonymous with LIS6, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, microlissencephaly, and a condition that essentially involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a microlissencephaly characterized by severe microcephaly, developmental delay, lissencephaly, pachygyria, and hypoplasia of the corpus callosum, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KATNB1 gene located on chromosome 16q21.

Lissencephaly 1 is a type of lissencephaly, autosomal dominant disease, and is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a lissencephaly characterized by an abnormally thick cortex, reduced or abnormal lamination, and diffuse neuronal heterotopia, which has its material basis in a mutation heterozygous in the PAFAH1B1 gene on chromosome 17p13.3. Furthermore, Lissencephaly 1 has the exact synonyms LIS1 and PAFAH1B1-related lissencephaly.

X-linked lissencephaly 2 is a type of lissencephaly, also classified as a type of X-linked monogenic disease and a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in X-linked inheritance. It is characterized by structural brain anomalies, early-onset intractable seizures, severe psychomotor retardation, and ambiguous genitalia, which are due to a mutation in the ARX gene on chromosome Xp21.3. Furthermore, X-linked lissencephaly 2 is known by several exact synonyms, including X-linked lissencephaly with abnormal genitalia, X-linked lissencephaly with ambiguous genitalia, X-linked lissencephaly-corpus callosum agenesis-genital anomalies syndrome, XLAG, and XLAG (X-linked lissencephaly with abnormal genitalia) syndrome, as well as XLIS2.

X-linked lissencephaly 1 is a type of lissencephaly, a type of X-linked monogenic disease, and a type of something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is characterized by classic lissencephaly and intellectual disability in males that has its material basis in mutation in the DCX gene on chromosome Xq23. Furthermore, X-linked lissencephaly 1 has the exact synonyms XLIS1 and lissencephaly type 1 due to doublecortin gene mutation.

Leber congenital amaurosis with early onset deafness (LCAEOD) is identified as a type of sensory system disease and also classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is acknowledged as something that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. LCAEOD is defined as a sensory system disease characterized by early-onset and severe photoreceptor and cochlear cell loss, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TUBB4B gene on chromosome 9q34.3.

Multiple benign circumferential skin creases on limbs is a type of skin disease characterized by benign circumferential skin creases, mainly on the limbs, due to folding of excess skin. It has exact synonyms including CCSF, Kunze-Riehm syndrome, circumferential skin creases, Kunze type, and congenital circumferential skin folds. Furthermore, it exactly matches GARD:3589 and OMIM:PS156610 in medical databases.

Congenital symmetric circumferential skin creases 1 (CSCSC1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is also characterized as having multiple benign circumferential skin creases on limbs. This condition fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, CSCSC1 is defined as a condition where multiple benign circumferential skin creases on limbs are observed, characterized by the folding of excess skin, which leads to ringed creases primarily on the limbs. It is also associated with intellectual disability, cleft palate, and dysmorphic features, all of which have their material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TUBB gene located on chromosome 6p21.33.

Congenital symmetric circumferential skin creases 2 (CSCSC2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by multiple benign circumferential skin creases on limbs, which result from folding of excess skin leading to ringed creases, primarily of the limbs. This condition is also associated with intellectual disability, cleft palate, and dysmorphic features. The material basis for this condition is at least partly attributed to autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a heterozygous mutation in the MAPRE2 gene on chromosome 18q12.1-q12.2.

Alopecia neurologic defects and endocrinopathy syndrome, which is also exactly known as ANE syndrome, ANES, and alopecia-progressive neurological defect-endocrinopathy syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by the presence of alopecia, neurologic defects, and endocrinopathy, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RBM28 gene located on chromosome 7q32.1.

Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis 3 (FSGS3) is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a specific form of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that is rooted in autosomal inheritance. This particular disease is defined by a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that results from a loss of function mutation in the CD2AP gene located on chromosome 6p12.3. Additionally, FSGS3 is also precisely known by its exact synonym, FSGS3.

Glutaric acidemia type 3, also precisely known as GA III, GA3, glutaric aciduria 3, glutaric aciduria III, glutaric aciduria type 3, or glutaryl-CoA oxidase deficiency, is classified both as an autosomal recessive disease and a peroxisomal disease. This condition is characterized by a specific type that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a peroxisomal disorder marked by the isolated accumulation of glutaric acid without other clinical phenotypes. This accumulation is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SUGCT gene located on chromosome 7p14.1.

The syndrome characterized by congenital heart defects, dysmorphic facial features, and intellectual developmental disorder is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of syndrome that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CDK13 gene on chromosome 7p14.1. Furthermore, this disorder is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms CDK13-Related CHDFIDD, CDK13-Related Disorder, and CHDFIDD.

17 beta hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 3 deficiency is an autosomal recessive disease that also manifests as a type of pseudohermaphroditism, essentially rooted in certain autosomal recessive inheritance mechanisms. It is specifically characterized by pseudohermaphroditism in males, which includes features like undermasculinization, hypoplastic-to-normal internal genitalia paired with female external genitalia, absence of a prostate, and impaired testicular synthesis of testosterone. This leads to insufficient formation of dihydrotestosterone during fetal development due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HSD17B3 gene located on chromosome 9q22. The condition is alternatively known by several exact synonyms, including 17-KSR deficiency, 17-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 3 deficiency, 17-ketoreductase deficiency, 17-ketosteroidreductase deficiency, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to 17-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 3 deficiency, male pseudohermaphroditism with gynecomastia, and neutral 17-beta-hydroxysteroid oxidoreductase deficiency.

Gapo syndrome is a syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease, which fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is precisely defined as a syndrome characterized by growth retardation, alopecia, pseudoanodontia, and ocular manifestations, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ANTXR1 gene located on chromosome 2p13.3. Additionally, Gapo syndrome is exactly synonymous with growth delay-alopecia-pseudoanodontia-optic atrophy syndrome.

Gaucher's disease type IIIC is a subtype of Gaucher's disease type III and is also classified under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific form of Gaucher's disease, known as type IIIC, is characterized by the additional presence of cardiovascular calcifications. This characteristic is due to homozygosity for an aspartic acid to histidine (D409H) mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. It is exactly synonymous with several terms including GD3C, Gaucher disease type 3C, Gaucher disease-ophthalmoplegia-cardiovascular calcification syndrome, Gaucher-like disease, and cardiovascular Gaucher disease.

Ghosal Hematodiaphyseal Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which particularly stems from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by increased bone density with predominant diaphyseal involvement and aregenerative corticosteroid-sensitive anemia. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in TBXAS1 on chromosome 7q34. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with Ghosal Hematodiaphyseal Dysplasia, Ghosal Syndrome, and Diaphyseal Dysplasia-Anemia Syndrome.

Glutathione synthetase deficiency of erythrocytes is a specific type of glutathione synthetase deficiency and an autosomal recessive disease, which is generally characterized by a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a glutathione synthetase deficiency characterized by hemolytic anemia and a deficiency in GSH that is limited to the red blood cells. Notably, nucleated cells are able to maintain normal or near-normal expression levels. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GSS gene located on chromosome 20q11.22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with glutathione synthetase deficiency without 5-oxoprolinuria.

Combined cellular and humoral immune defects with granulomas (CCHIDG), also known as CID due to RAG 1/2 deficiency, combined immunodeficiency due to RAG 1/2 deficiency, combined immunodeficiency with granulomatosis, and combined immunodeficiency with skin granulomas, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of combined immunodeficiency. It is characterized by combined cellular and humoral deficiencies along with multiple granulomas, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RAG1 gene or the RAG2 gene on chromosome 11p12. This condition is also classified based on its phenotypic characteristics, which include granuloma formation, and its genetic basis, which involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Hepatic venoocclusive disease with immunodeficiency (VODI), also known as hepatic veno-occlusive disease-immunodeficiency syndrome, is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a syndrome that includes severe hypogammaglobulinemia, combined T and B cell immunodeficiency, the absence of lymph node germinal centers, absent tissue plasma cells, hepatic vascular occlusion, and fibrosis. This syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SP110 gene on chromosome 2q37.1.

Homocystinuria megaloblastic anemia cblE type is a type of autosomal recessive disease, amino acid metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the failure of cells to incorporate methyltetrahydrofolate into methionine with somewhat variable features that include delayed psychomotor development, hypotonia, megaloblastic anemia, homocystinuria, and hypomethioninemia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MTRR gene on chromosome 5p15.31. It is also known by several exact synonyms including HMAE, functional methionine synthase deficiency type cblE, homocystinuria-megaloblastic anemia due to defect in cobalamin metabolism cblE complementation type, methylcobalamin deficiency, cblE type, and vitamin B12-responsive homocystinuria, cblE type.

Homocystinuria megaloblastic anemia cblG type is a type of autosomal recessive disease and amino acid metabolic disorder that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the failure of cells to incorporate methyltetrahydrofolate into methionine, impaired methionine synthase activity in the presence of a reducing agent, and somewhat variable features. These features include delayed psychomotor development, hypotonia, megaloblastic anemia, homocystinuria, and hypomethioninemia, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in MTR on chromosome 1q43. This condition also has exact synonyms including HMAG, homocystinuria-megaloblastic anemia due to defect in cobalamin metabolism cblG complementation type, homocystinuria-megaloblastic anemia, cblG complementation type, and methylcobalamin deficiency, cblG type.

Hydroxykynureninuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease, amino acid metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by impaired tryptophan metabolism that results in high urinary excretion of kynurenine, xanthurenic acid, and 3-hydroxykynurenine due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KYNU gene on chromosome 2q22.2. Additionally, hydroxykynureninuria is exactly synonymous with kynureninase deficiency and xanthurenic aciduria.

N-acetylglutamate synthase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a urea cycle disorder. It is characterized by the accumulation of ammonia in the blood due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NAGS gene on chromosome 17q21.31. This condition is also known as N-acetyl glutamate synthetase deficiency, N-acetylglutamate synthetase deficiency, NAG synthetase deficiency, NAGS deficiency, and hyperammonemia due to N-acetylglutamate synthase deficiency. It is essentially a disorder that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Leydig cell hypoplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, also classified as a type of pseudohermaphroditism, and it can be described as a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a pseudohermaphroditism that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LHCGR gene on chromosome 2p16.3. Additionally, Leydig cell hypoplasia is exactly synonymous with 46,XY DSD (Disorder of Sex Development) due to LH (Luteinizing Hormone) resistance or LHB (Luteinizing Hormone Beta) deficiency, which can also be expressed as 46,XY disorder of sex development due to luteinizing hormone resistance or luteinizing hormone beta subunit deficiency.

Leydig cell hypoplasia type I is a specific form of Leydig cell hypoplasia and is also classified within the broader category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a type of Leydig cell hypoplasia characterized by 46,XY male pseudohermaphroditism, which includes low testosterone levels, high LH levels, a total lack of responsiveness to LH/CG challenge, absence of breast development, and the absence of secondary male sex characteristics. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous complete inactivation mutations in the LHCGR gene located on chromosome 2p16.3. Leydig cell hypoplasia type I is also known by several exact synonyms including 46,XY DSD (Disorder of Sex Development) due to complete LH receptor inactivation, 46,XY DSD due to complete LH resistance, 46,XY DSD due to complete luteinizing hormone receptor inactivation, 46,XY DSD due to complete luteinizing hormone resistance, Leydig cell hypoplasia due to complete LH receptor inactivation, and Leydig cell hypoplasia due to complete luteinizing hormone receptor inactivation, as well as Leydig cell hypoplasia due to complete luteinizing hormone resistance.

Leydig cell hypoplasia type II is a specific form of Leydig cell hypoplasia. It is categorized under conditions that fundamentally stem from autosomal recessive inheritance. This type of Leydig cell hypoplasia is defined by a range of symptoms that vary from micropenis to severe hypospadias and bifid scrotum, all of which are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous partial inactivation mutations in the LHCGR gene located on chromosome 2p16.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including 46,XY DSD (Disorder of Sex Development) due to partial LH (Luteinizing Hormone) receptor inactivation, 46,XY DSD due to partial LH resistance, 46,XY DSD due to partial luteinizing hormone resistance, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to partial LH receptor inactivation, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to partial LH resistance, 46,XY disorder of sex development due to partial luteinizing hormone resistance, Leydig cell hypoplasia due to partial LH receptor inactivation, Leydig cell hypoplasia due to partial LH resistance, Leydig cell hypoplasia due to partial luteinizing hormone receptor inactivation, and Leydig cell hypoplasia due to partial luteinizing hormone resistance.

Leucine sensitive hypoglycemia of infancy (LIH), also known as leucine-induced hypoglycemia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, amino acid metabolic disorder, and hypoglycemia. It is characterized by a condition that starts during infancy and involves abnormal blood glucose concentration with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the development of hypoglycemia after high-protein feedings or leucine infusion, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the SUR1 gene on chromosome 11p15.1.

Hypoinsulinemic hypoglycemia with hemihypertrophy (HIHGHH), also known as hypoinsulinemic hypoglycemia and body hemihypertrophy, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and hypoglycemia. It is characterized by its autosomal dominant inheritance, abnormal blood glucose concentration, and it features hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia as a disease characteristic. This inherited metabolic disorder is notably defined by neonatal macrosomia, asymmetrical overgrowth, and recurrent, severe hypoinsulinemic hypoglycemia in infancy, which stems from a heterozygous activating mutation in the AKT2 gene on chromosome 19q13.2.

Woodhouse Sakati Syndrome is an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of syndromes, specifically those having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by hypogonadism, alopecia, diabetes mellitus, intellectual deficit, and extrapyramidal signs with choreoathetoid movements and dystonia, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DCAF17 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. This syndrome is also known by exact synonyms including diabetes-hypogonadism-deafness-intellectual disability syndrome, diabetes-hypogonadism-hearing loss-intellectual disability syndrome, hypogonadism, alopecia, diabetes mellitus, mental retardation, deafness, and extrapyramidal syndrome, as well as progressive extrapyramidal disorder with primary hypogonadism, mental retardation, and alopecia.

Iminoglycinuria is classified as a type of digenic disease, and it is also recognized as a type of renal tubular transport disease. This condition is known for having a material basis in digenic inheritance. Specifically, iminoglycinuria is defined as a renal tubular transport disease that is characterized by the impaired reabsorption by renal tubes of proline, hydroxyproline, and glycine, leading to elevated urine levels of these imino acids and glycine. The material basis for this disease involves a homozygous mutation in the SLC36A2 gene on chromosome 5q33.1, combined with either a heterozygous mutation in the SLC6A20 gene on chromosome 3p21.31 or a homozygous mutation in the SLC6A19 gene on chromosome 5p15.33.

Nephrotic syndrome type 23, also known exactly as NPHS23, is a familial nephrotic syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is specifically characterized by the onset of proteinuria during the first or second decade of life, mesangial hypercellularity, focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, and effacement of podocyte foot processes. The basis of this condition lies in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KIRREL1 gene located on chromosome 1q23.1. This syndrome is a manifestation of certain autosomal recessive inheritance patterns.

Nephrotic syndrome type 21, which has the exact synonym NPHS21, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, familial nephrotic syndrome, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome characterized by the onset of rapidly progressive kidney dysfunction in the first year of life, proteinuria, and diffuse mesangial sclerosis. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AVIL gene on chromosome 12q14.1.

Nephrotic syndrome type 22, also precisely known as NPHS22, is a familial nephrotic syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by the onset of progressive kidney dysfunction in infancy, coupled with symptoms such as edema, hypoproteinemia, proteinuria, microscopic hematuria, effacement of the podocyte foot processes, glomerulosclerosis, and thickening of the glomerular basement membrane. This syndrome is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NOS1AP gene located on chromosome 1q23.3.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 18, also known precisely as POF18 or premature ovarian failure 18, is a specific type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency characterized by irregular menstrual cycles and the cessation of menstruation in the third decade of life, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in C14orf39 on chromosome 14q23.1. This condition is also categorized as a type of disorder that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 52, also precisely known as SPGF52, is classified as a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific kind of spermatogenic failure that is associated with non-obstructive azoospermia resulting from meiotic arrest at the spermatocyte stage. This condition fundamentally arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C14orf39 gene located on chromosome 14q23.1. Furthermore, spermatogenic failure 52 is recognized as a condition that inherently possesses a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 49, which is an autosomal recessive disease and a type of spermatogenic failure, inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the sperm flagella, leading to significantly reduced or no progressive motility, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP58 gene located on chromosome 10q25.1. Furthermore, spermatogenic failure 49 is exactly synonymous with SPGF98.

Spermatogenic failure 50 is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spermatogenic failure 50 is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by azoospermia due to meiotic arrest at prophase I, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the XRCC2 gene on chromosome 7q36.1. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 50 is exactly synonymous with SPGF50.

Spermatogenic failure 51 is a specific type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by severe asthenoteratozoospermia with multiple morphological abnormalities of the flagella, resulting in reduced to absent motility due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP91 gene located on chromosome 3q13.33. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 51 is exactly synonymous with SPGF51.

X-linked spermatogenic failure 3 is a type of X-linked recessive disease, spermatogenic failure, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by asthenoteratozoospermia with multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella that has a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the CFAP47 gene on chromosome Xp21.1. Additionally, X-linked spermatogenic failure 3 has the exact synonym SPGFX3.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 93 (DEE93), also known as IECEE3 or infantile or early childhood epileptic encephalopathy 3, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE93 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that is marked by delayed psychomotor development, early-onset refractory seizures, and impaired intellectual development, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP6V1A gene located on chromosome 3q13.31.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with involuntary movements, also exactly known as NEDIM, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and movement disease. It is characterized by being a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits a phenotype of neurodevelopmental abnormality. Specifically, NEDIM is defined as a movement disease marked by delayed psychomotor development and onset in infancy or childhood of hyperkinetic involuntary movements, such as chorea and athetosis, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in the GNAO1 gene located on chromosome 16q13.

Immunodeficiency 79, also precisely known as IMD79, is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically falling under the category of T cell deficiency. It is described as a disorder that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The disease is detailed as a T cell deficiency that manifests through childhood onset of recurrent and stubborn skin warts due to uncontrolled viral infection with human papillomavirus, coupled with the absence of the CD4 antigen on T cells, monocytes, and dendritic cells. This condition is a result of either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CD4 gene located on chromosome 12p13.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 19, also precisely known as POF19, POI19, and premature ovarian failure 19, is categorized as a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by a condition of primary ovarian insufficiency that notably involves irregular menses ceasing in the third decade of life, stemming from a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HSF2BP gene located on chromosome 21q22. This condition is a manifestation of something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 53, also exactly known as SPGF53, is a type of spermatogenic failure and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by infertility due to the absence of oocyte activation and ultrastructural abnormalities of the sperm head, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ACTL9 gene located on chromosome 19p13.2. Moreover, spermatogenic failure 53 is defined as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and has the exact synonym SED. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by skeletal dysplasia mainly involving the spine and proximal epiphyses, resulting in shortening of the trunk and limbs.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Stanescu type is a form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, which is also classified as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized by the accumulation of glycoprotein in chondrocytes, progressive joint contracture leading to premature degenerative joint disease, generalized platyspondyly, a hypoplastic pelvis, epiphyseal flattening with metaphyseal splaying of the long bones, and enlarged phalangeal epimetaphyses of the hands. The genetic basis for this disorder is a heterozygous mutation in the COL2A1 gene located on chromosome 12q13.11. Additionally, Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Stanescu type is precisely synonymous with SED Stanescu type and SEDSTN, indicating that these terms refer to the same condition.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Kimberley type is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACAN gene on chromosome 15q26.1. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with SEDK and is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Kondo-Fu type is a form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a specific kind of condition that necessarily has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular disorder is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MBTPS1 gene located on chromosome 16q23.3-q24.1. It is also known by the exact synonyms "SED with elevated blood lysosomal enzymes" and "SEDKF."

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia characterized by impaired growth of the bones of the spine and the ends of the long bones, which becomes apparent after birth.

Autosomal dominant spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda (SEDT) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance patterns. Specifically, SEDT is defined by a heterozygous mutation in a region of chromosome 12q13, highlighting its genetic basis.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia with punctate corneal dystrophy is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia characterized by spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and punctate dystrophy of the full depth of the corneal stroma.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia brachydactyly and distinctive speech is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, brachydactyly, and distinctive speech. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including Fantasy Island syndrome, SED-BDS, SED-brachydactyly and distinctive speech, Tattoo dysplasia, and spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, Cantu type.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Nishimura type is a type of autosomal dominant disease, as well as a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, and it is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia characterized by disproportionate short stature with short limbs, small hands and feet, midface hypoplasia with a small nose, mild spondylar dysplasia, delayed epiphyseal ossification of the hip and knee, and severe brachydactyly with cone-shaped phalangeal epiphyses. This condition is caused by a heterozygous gain-of-function mutation in the MIR140 gene located on chromosome 16q22.1.
