Furthermore, Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia Nishimura type has the exact synonym SEDN.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda with characteristic facies is a specific type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease and is defined by a condition that fundamentally involves autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda is characterized by skeletal dysplasia, microcephaly, unusual facies, and moderate developmental delay, distinguishing it within its broader disease category.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, sensorineural hearing loss, intellectual developmental disorder, and Leber congenital amaurosis is a syndrome that is also known as SHILCA syndrome. This condition is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is characterized by a group of symptoms that include early-onset retinal degeneration, sensorineural hearing loss, short stature, vertebral anomalies, epiphyseal dysplasia, and motor and intellectual delay. The material basis for this syndrome involves homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NMNAT1 gene on chromosome 1p36.22, indicating its autosomal recessive inheritance nature.

Autosomal recessive spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda Leroy Spranger type is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda, and something that fundamentally has a basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with a late-onset of short-trunk type of short stature, abnormal spinal curvature, and minor leg deformities.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda with intellectual disability is a specific type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda, which falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is defined as a form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, associated with mild to moderate intellectual disability. Additionally, it is a manifestation of a disorder that fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Autosomal recessive spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda, and a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by short stature, flat vertebrae, and severe hip disease, which defines this specific form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia with coronal craniosynostosis, cataracts, cleft palate, and intellectual disability is a type of syndrome. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, craniosynostosis, cataracts, cleft palate, and intellectual disability.
Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by platyspondyly (flattened vertebrae) and marked hip and knee metaphyseal lesions.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Algerian type is a specific form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia characterized by several distinct features including dwarfism, genu valgum deformity, progressive kypho-scoliosis, wrist deformity, myopia, and severe metaphyseal dysplasia, accompanied by moderate spinal changes and minimal changes in the hands and feet. This condition is also precisely known by two other names: spondylometaphyseal dysplasia with severe genu valgum and spondylometaphyseal dysplasia, Schmidt type.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia corner fracture type (SMDCF), also known as spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Sutcliffe type, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. More specifically, SMDCF is defined as a spondylometaphyseal dysplasia characterized by flake-like, triangular, or curvilinear ossification centers at the edges of irregular metaphyses that simulate fractures, and this condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FN1 gene located on chromosome 2q35.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Sedaghatian type is a specific form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia and falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by neonatal lethality, severe metaphyseal chondrodysplasia with mild limb shortening, platyspondyly, delayed epiphyseal ossification, irregular iliac crests, pulmonary hemorrhage, severe hypotonia, and cardiorespiratory problems. The disease has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GPX4 gene on chromosome 19p13.3. Furthermore, Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Sedaghatian type is also known by its exact synonyms: SMDS, Sedaghatian chondrodysplasia, and congenital lethal metaphyseal chondrodysplasia.

Axial spondylometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, spondylometaphyseal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondylometaphyseal dysplasia characterized by postnatal growth failure, metaphyseal changes of truncal-juxtatruncal bones, and retinal abnormalities, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CFAP410 gene on chromosome 21q22.3. Axial spondylometaphyseal dysplasia also has exact synonyms SMD axial and SMDAX.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia with cone rod dystrophy (SMD-CRD), also known exactly as SMDCRD and spondylometaphyseal dysplasia-cone-rod dystrophy syndrome, is a specific type of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, which implies that it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by a combination of physical and visual impairments. These include postnatal growth deficiency, profound short stature, rhizomelia with bowing of the lower extremities, platyspondyly with anterior vertebral protrusions, and progressive metaphyseal irregularity and cupping with shortened tubular bones. Additionally, individuals with this condition experience early-onset progressive visual impairment due to a pigmentary maculopathy and evidence of cone-rod dysfunction as demonstrated by electroretinography. The genetic basis for this disease involves homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PCYT1A gene located on chromosome 3q29.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia type A4 is a type of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. It is defined as a spondylometaphyseal dysplasia characterized by severe metaphyseal changes of the femoral neck and ovoid, flattened vertebral bodies with anterior tongue-like deformities.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia East African type is a type of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by oval vertebral bodies with wide, bracket-shaped metaphyses and small, round epiphyses without anterior tonguing of the vertebral bodies.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia with corneal dystrophy (SMDCD) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by a combination of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia and corneal dystrophy, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLCB3 gene located on chromosome 11q13.1. This condition also falls under the category of diseases that have at least a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia Megarbane-Dagher-Melike type is a specific form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia and falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by a particular genetic basis, being a result of either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PAM16 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. This type of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia is also known by its exact synonyms, which include Megarbane-Dagher-Melike type chondrodysplasia and SMDMDM, indicating its specific classification within the broader category of diseases that generally have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia with bowed forearms and facial dysmorphism is a specific type of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. This condition is characterized by a set of features including short stature, hyperlordosis, bowed legs, shortening and bowing of the forearms, an abnormal facial appearance, and radiographic changes that are characteristic of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia. It is also known by exact synonyms such as SMD with bowed forearms and facial dysmorphism and spondylometaphyseal dysplasia-bowed forearms-facial dysmorphism syndrome.

Mahvash disease is a type of autosomal recessive and endocrine pancreas disease, which is also characterized by its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an endocrine pancreas disease marked by pancreatic alpha cell hyperplasia, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors, and elevated serum glucagon levels, which arise from homozygous or compound heterozygous inactivating mutations of the GCGR gene on chromosome 17q25.3. Mahvash disease is exactly synonymous with GCGR-related hyperglucagonemia and also known as nesidioblastosis, alpha cell hyperplasia, microglucagonoma, and nonfunctioning islet cell tumor. Additionally, it has an exact match with the OMIM identifier 619290.

Sarcosinemia is an autosomal recessive disease and a type of amino acid metabolic disorder. It is characterized by a condition that arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, sarcosinemia is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by increased concentrations of sarcosine in plasma and urine, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SARDH gene on chromosome 9q34.2. Sarcosinemia is also known by several exact synonyms including SARCOS, SARD deficiency, SARDH deficiency, demethylation defect of N-methylglycine, and sarcosine dehydrogenase complex deficiency.

Central precocious puberty is a type of endocrine system disease characterized by the early activation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis, which results in the development of secondary sexual characteristics before the age of 8 years in girls and 9 years in boys. It has the exact synonyms CPP and gonadotropin-dependent precocious puberty.

Central precocious puberty 2 (CPPB2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of central precocious puberty, characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a central precocious puberty that arises from a heterozygous mutation on the paternal allele of the MKRN3 gene on chromosome 15q11.2.

Central precocious puberty 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, central precocious puberty, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a central precocious puberty that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KISS1R gene on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, Central precocious puberty 1 is exactly synonymous with CPPB1.

Male infertility due to acephalic spermatozoa is a type of spermatogenic failure, which is characterized by male infertility caused by a majority of spermatozoa lacking heads. This condition is also exactly synonymous with acephalic spermatozoa syndrome.

Male infertility due to globozoospermia is a type of spermatogenic failure characterized by the majority of spermatozoa having round heads and acrosome defects, leading to male infertility. This condition is also exactly synonymous with globozoospermia syndrome.
Brain small vessel disease is a type of brain disease characterized by abnormalities in the small blood vessels in the brain.

Brain Small Vessel Disease 2 (BSVD2), also known as porencephaly 2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific category of brain small vessel disease. It is characterized by a disturbed vascular supply to the brain leading to cerebral degeneration, porencephaly, and hemiplegia, seizures, and intellectual disability with variable severity. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL4A2 gene located on chromosome 13q34. Furthermore, it is identified as a disease that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Brain Small Vessel Disease 3 (BSVD3) is a type of Brain Small Vessel Disease and an autosomal recessive disease, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by impaired basement membrane morphology that results in increased fragility of cerebral blood vessels, leading to an increased risk of intracranial bleeds of variable severity. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COLGALT1 gene located on chromosome 19p13.11.

Methemoglobinemia and ambiguous genitalia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, disorder of sexual development, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by a disorder of sexual development that features severely reduced 17,20-lyase activity of CYP17A1, a deficiency in sex steroids without affecting glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid reserves, absent or disturbed pubertal development, and mild to severe methemoglobinemia. The condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CYB5A gene on chromosome 18q22.3. Methemoglobinemia and ambiguous genitalia is also known by its exact synonyms: METAG, methemoglobinemia due to deficiency of cytochrome b5, methemoglobinemia type IV, and pure isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency.

Schindler disease is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a lysosomal storage disease that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a lysosomal storage disease that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NAGA gene on chromosome 22q13.2. Schindler disease is also exactly synonymous with NAGA deficiency and alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency.

Schindler Disease Type 1 is a specific type of Schindler Disease, characterized by an infantile onset of neuroaxonal dystrophy. This condition arises due to either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NAGA gene located on chromosome 22q13.2. Furthermore, Schindler Disease Type 1 is precisely synonymous with both NAGA deficiency type 1 and alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency type 1.

Kanzaki disease is a type of Schindler disease characterized by the adult-onset of angiokeratoma corporis diffusum and mild intellectual impairment. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding alpha-N-galactosaminidase (NAGA) on chromosome 22q13. Kanzaki disease is precisely synonymous with NAGA deficiency type 2, adult-onset alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency, and alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency type 2.

Schindler Disease Type 3, which is a type of Schindler Disease, is characterized by mild to moderate neurologic manifestations that begin after infancy but earlier than in Schindler Disease Type 3. This specific condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NAGA gene on chromosome 22q13.2. Additionally, Schindler Disease Type 3 is precisely synonymous with both NAGA deficiency type 3 and alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase deficiency type 3.

Alacrima achalasia and impaired intellectual development syndrome (AAMR), also known as alacrima, achalasia, and mental retardation syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also categorized as a congenital disorder of glycosylation and is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation that manifests in infancy with alacrima, achalasia, and impaired intellectual development, without adrenal insufficiency. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GMPPA gene located on chromosome 2q35.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1 is a specific type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia, characterized by spinal cord anterior horn cell degeneration combined with pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Norman disease, PCH1, pontocerebellar hypoplasia with anterior horn cell disease, and pontocerebellar hypoplasia with infantile spinal muscular atrophy.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1d (PCH1D) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1. It is defined as a variation of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1 characterized by severe hypotonia and motor neuronopathy, which are detectable at birth or in infancy. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EXOSC9 gene located on chromosome 4q27. Additionally, pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1d is also recognized as being a type of condition that inherently involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 11 (PCH11) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is defined as a form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by severely delayed psychomotor development with intellectual disability and poor speech, microcephaly, dysmorphic features, and pontocerebellar hypoplasia observable on brain imaging. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBC1D23 gene located on chromosome 3q12.1-q12.2. Additionally, it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 14 (PCH14) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is characterized by a congenital onset of progressive microcephaly, poor or absent psychomotor development, and severely impaired intellectual development. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PPIL1 gene located on chromosome 6p21.2. Additionally, pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 14 is described as a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 15 (PCH15) is a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is specifically defined by a pontocerebellar hypoplasia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CDC40 gene located on chromosome 6q21.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 12 is classified as a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia and is an autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 12 is defined as a pontocerebellar hypoplasia with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COASY gene on chromosome 17q21.2. It is also exactly synonymous with COASY-related pontocerebellar hypoplasia and PCH12.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2 is a specific type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia, which is defined as a pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by pontocerebellar hypoplasia and progressive neocortical atrophy. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with PCH2.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2f, which has the exact synonym PCH2F, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2. It is defined by progressive microcephaly and variable neurologic signs and symptoms, which stem from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TSEN15 gene on chromosome 1q25.3. This condition exemplifies a disorder that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1e, also known precisely as PCH1E, is identified as a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1 and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. Specifically, it is a form of a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1e encompasses a pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1 distinguished by the onset shortly after birth of severe hypotonia and respiratory insufficiency, with most patients succumbing to the condition within weeks of birth. This disease has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A46 gene located on chromosome 5q22.1.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1f (PCH1F) is a specific subtype of autosomal recessive disease and pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1, characterized by being a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia is defined by features such as hypotonia, global developmental delay, poor overall growth, and dysmorphic facial features, all resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EXOSC1 gene located on chromosome 10q24.1.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 13, also known precisely as PCH13, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 13 is distinguished by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with absent speech, microcephaly, and progressive atrophy of the cerebellar vermis and brainstem. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VPS51 gene located on chromosome 11q13.1.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 16 (PCH16) is a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, PCH16 is characterized by hypotonia and severe global developmental delay apparent from early infancy, and it has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MINPP1 gene located on chromosome 10q23.2.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1c (PCH1C) is categorized as a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1, which falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is specifically associated with conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. The disease is defined by severe muscle weakness and failure to thrive, noticeable in the first months of life, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EXOSC8 gene on chromosome 13q13.3.

Spermatogenic failure 54, also exactly known as SPGF54, is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of spermatogenic failure. It is associated with a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Spermatogenic failure 54 is defined by male infertility due to oligoteratoasthenozoospermia, which involves markedly reduced sperm counts and severely reduced or absent sperm motility, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CATIP gene located on chromosome 2q35.

Spermatogenic failure 56 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure, which is also characterized as having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure that leads to male infertility due to multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella with severely reduced sperm motility. This condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DNAH10 gene located on chromosome 12q24.31. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 56 is exactly synonymous with SPGF56.

Spermatogenic failure 55, also known exactly as SPGF55, is classified as a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is specifically identified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by male infertility, which is attributed to asthenozoospermia, where there is severely reduced sperm motility. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SPAG17 gene located on chromosome 1p12.

Spermatogenic failure 57, also known exactly as SPGF57, is a type of spermatogenic failure and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific kind of autosomal recessive inheritance that has a material basis in certain conditions. The definition of spermatogenic failure 57 outlines it as a spermatogenic failure marked by male infertility, which results from error-prone meiosis of germ cells and spermatogenic arrest at the late pachytene stage. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PNLDC1 gene located on chromosome 6q25.3.

Tatton Brown Rahman Syndrome (TBRS) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndromic intellectual disability, and is characterized by a type that involves autosomal dominant inheritance and neurodevelopmental delay. It is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability that features tall stature, distinctive facial appearance, and impaired intellectual development due to a heterozygous mutation in the DNMT3A gene on chromosome 2p23.3. Additionally, TBRS is also known by its exact synonyms: DNMT3A Overgrowth Syndrome, DOS, TBRS, and Tatton-Brown-Rahman Overgrowth Syndrome.

Craniotubular dysplasia Ikegawa type, which has the exact synonym CTDI, is a form of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of craniodiaphyseal dysplasia. This condition is characterized by a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Craniotubular dysplasia Ikegawa type is defined as a craniodiaphyseal dysplasia marked by childhood-onset short stature, coupled with macrocephaly, dolichocephaly, or a prominent forehead. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM53 gene located on chromosome 1p34.1.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 80 (SPG80) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it is also classified as a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia, indicating that it at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific hereditary spastic paraplegia is characterized by a juvenile-onset of progressive spasticity and hyperreflexia, mainly affecting the lower limbs, and it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the UBAP1 gene on chromosome 9p13.3. Furthermore, hereditary spastic paraplegia 80 is exactly synonymous with spastic paraplegia 80 autosomal dominant.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 86 (SPG86, also known as spastic paraplegia 86 autosomal recessive) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by an early childhood onset of global developmental delay and early-onset progressive spasticity, mainly affecting the lower limbs but also impacting the upper limbs. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ABHD16A gene on chromosome 6p21.33.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 82 (SPG82) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by the fact that it at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, SPG82 is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by onset in infancy of global developmental delay, significant motor impairment, and progressive spasticity mainly affecting the lower limbs. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PCYT2 gene on chromosome 17q25.3. Additionally, hereditary spastic paraplegia 82 is also exactly synonymous with "spastic paraplegia 82 autosomal recessive."

Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia 79b (HSP79b) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begins during juvenile onset. HSP79b is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by the onset of spastic paraplegia and optic atrophy in the first decade of life, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UCHL1 gene on chromosome 4p13. HSP79b is also known by several exact synonyms, including SPG79B, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 79B, early-onset progressive neurodegeneration-blindness-ataxia-spasticity syndrome, and spastic paraplegia 79 autosomal recessive.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 85 (SPG85, also known as spastic paraplegia 85 autosomal recessive) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia, which is a category of autosomal recessive diseases. It specifically stems from autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating that it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive genetic mechanism. This particular condition is characterized by motor symptoms such as spasticity and hyperreflexia of the lower limbs that manifest in the first few years of life. The underlying cause of hereditary spastic paraplegia 85 is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RNF170 gene located on chromosome 8p11.21.

Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia 83 (HSP83) is a type of Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease, meaning it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by progressive lower limb spasticity leading to gait instability, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HPDL gene located on chromosome 1p34.1. HSP83 is also known by its exact synonyms, SPG83 and spastic paraplegia 83 autosomal recessive.

Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia 84 (SPG84), also known as spastic paraplegia 84 autosomal recessive, is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by an onset in the first two decades of life, where individuals experience slowly progressive walking difficulties due to lower limb weakness, stiffness, and spasticity. The disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PI4KA gene on chromosome 22q11.21.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 78 (SPG78) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and specifically by spasticity and muscle weakness of the lower limbs. This condition is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ATP13A2 gene on chromosome 1p36.13. Additionally, hereditary spastic paraplegia 78 is exactly synonymous with SPG78 and spastic paraplegia 78 autosomal recessive.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 81 (SPG81) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, as well as a specific form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It falls under the category of conditions that, at the very least, have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. SPG81 is characterized by its onset in infancy, delayed motor development, progressive spasticity, and other neurologic impairments. These manifestations are due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SELENOI gene located on chromosome 2p23.3. Additionally, hereditary spastic paraplegia 81 is also known by several exact synonyms, including autosomal recessive complex SPG due to Kennedy pathway dysfunction, autosomal recessive complex spastic paraplegia due to Kennedy pathway dysfunction, and spastic paraplegia 81 autosomal recessive.

Spermatogenic failure 61 (SPGF61) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific instance of spermatogenic failure, which fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by male infertility due to nonobstructive azoospermia with complete meiotic arrest at the primary spermatocyte stage. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the STAG3 gene located on chromosome 7q22.1.

Spermatogenic failure 62 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure, indicating that it is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by male infertility due to nonobstructive azoospermia with complete metaphase arrest at the spermatocyte stage, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RNF212 gene on chromosome 4p16.3. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 62 is exactly synonymous with SPGF62.

Spermatogenic failure 58, which has the exact synonym SPGF58, is identified as a type of spermatogenic failure and falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is also recognized as a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific spermatogenic failure is characterized by multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella and presents with immotile or severely reduced progressive motility of sperm. This condition arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IFT74 gene located on chromosome 9p21.2.

Spermatogenic failure 64 is a type of spermatogenic failure, autosomal recessive disease, and anything that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by male infertility due to oligoasthenoteratozoospermia or nonobstructive azoospermia, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FBXO43 gene on chromosome 8q22.2. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 64 has the exact synonym SPGF64.

Spermatogenic failure 65, which has the exact synonym SPGF65, is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and spermatogenic failure. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure that leads to male infertility due to asthenoteratozoospermia, which involves severely reduced or absent progressive sperm motility and multiple morphologic abnormalities of the flagella. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DHND1 gene on chromosome 11p15.4. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 65 is considered a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Spermatogenic failure 60 is a type of spermatogenic failure, which is an autosomal recessive disease. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spermatogenic failure 60 is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by male infertility due to nonobstructive azoospermia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TERB1 gene on chromosome 16q22.1. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 60 has the exact synonym SPGF 60.

Spermatogenic failure 63 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a subset of spermatogenic failures. It is characterized by a specific condition that arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spermatogenic failure 63 is defined as a spermatogenic failure that leads to male infertility, which is a result of severe oligozoospermia with markedly reduced progressive sperm motility. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RPL10L gene located on chromosome 14q21.2. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 63 is exactly synonymous with SPGF63.

Spermatogenic failure 59 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, spermatogenic failure, and something that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by male infertility due to nonobstructive azoospermia, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TERB2 gene on chromosome 15q21.1. Additionally, spermatogenic failure 59 has the exact synonym SPGF59.

Short stature, facial dysmorphism, and skeletal anomalies with or without cardiac anomalies represent a condition that falls under multiple categories: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a syndrome, and something that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by reduced growth, thin and short long bones, distinctive facial dysmorphism, dental and skeletal abnormalities, and the absence of developmental delay or intellectual disability. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SCUBE3 gene located on chromosome 6p21.31. Additionally, this condition is precisely referred to by the acronym SSFSC.

The Congenital Anomalies of Kidney and Urinary Tract Syndrome, which may or may not be accompanied by hearing loss, abnormal ears, or developmental delay, is recognized as a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and is characterized by at least having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as a condition marked by various congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract along with a variable presentation of ear abnormalities, hearing loss, and global developmental delay, which stems from a heterozygous mutation in the PBX1 gene on chromosome 1q23.3 or the deletion of a genomic region that includes the PBX1 gene. Additionally, this syndrome is precisely referred to by the acronym CAKUTHED.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 6 is a specific type of spondylocostal dysostosis and is also categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spondylocostal dysostosis 6 is defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RIPPLY2 gene located on chromosome 6q14.2. Furthermore, this condition is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms SCDO6 and autosomal recessive spondylocostal dysostosis 6.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 3 (SCDO3), also known exactly as autosomal recessive spondylocostal dysostosis 3, is a type of spondylocostal dysostosis and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a specific material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LFNG gene on chromosome 7p22.3.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 2 is a type of spondylocostal dysostosis, an autosomal recessive disease, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MESP2 gene on chromosome 15q26.1. Furthermore, spondylocostal dysostosis 2 is exactly synonymous with SCDO2 and autosomal recessive spondylocostal dysostosis 2.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 5, which has the exact synonym SCDO5, is a type of spondylocostal dysostosis and also falls under the category of autosomal genetic diseases. It is specifically characterized as a disorder that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that arises due to heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBX6 gene located on chromosome 16p11.2.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 4 is a type of spondylocostal dysostosis and an autosomal recessive disease, which also fits the broader category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that has its material basis in heterozygous or compound homozygous mutation in the HES7 gene on chromosome 17p13.1. Furthermore, spondylocostal dysostosis 4 is exactly synonymous with SCDO4 and autosomal recessive spondylocostal dysostosis 4.

Spondylocostal dysostosis 1, which has the exact synonyms SCDO1 and autosomal recessive spondylocostal dysostosis 1, is a type of spondylocostal dysostosis, as well as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, spondylocostal dysostosis 1 is defined as a spondylocostal dysostosis that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DLL3 gene located on chromosome 19q13.2.

Coffin-Siris Syndrome 8 (CSS8) is a subtype of Coffin-Siris Syndrome, which is characterized by variable degrees of impaired intellectual development, including speech impairment, hypotonia, feeding difficulties, and behavioral abnormalities, as well as a variable occurrence of other dysmorphic features. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SMARCC2 gene on chromosome 12q13. Additionally, Coffin-Siris Syndrome 8 is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance. CSS8 is also an exact synonym for Coffin-Siris Syndrome 8.

Coffin Siris Syndrome 5 (CSS5) is a subtype of Coffin Siris Syndrome and also falls under the category of conditions with a material basis at least partially in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Coffin-Siris syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability, coarse facial features, and hypoplasia of the distal phalanges, particularly the fifth digit, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the SMARCE1 gene located on chromosome 17q21.2.

Coffin-Siris Syndrome 7 (CSS7) is a type of Coffin-Siris Syndrome and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Coffin-Siris syndrome characterized by global developmental delay with mild to moderate intellectual disability, speech impairment, behavioral abnormalities, poor overall growth, coarse facial features, and hypoplastic fifth toenails, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DPF2 gene on chromosome 11q13.1.

Coffin Siris Syndrome 12 (CSS12) is a type of Coffin Siris Syndrome and also a type of condition that at least has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Coffin-Siris syndrome characterized by global developmental delay with variably impaired intellectual development, speech and language delay, and behavioral abnormalities, such as autism or hyperactivity, that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the BICRA gene on chromosome 19q13.33.

Coffin-Siris Syndrome 10 (CSS10) is a type of Coffin-Siris Syndrome and can also be characterized as a type of condition that typically involves some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined by a range of symptoms including mild to severe intellectual disability, global developmental delay, mild but distinct facial dysmorphism, fifth finger clinodactyly, and small stature, all attributable to a heterozygous mutation in the SOX4 gene located on chromosome 6p22.3. Furthermore, CSS10 is exactly synonymous with Coffin-Siris Syndrome 10.

Coffin Siris Syndrome 11 (CSS11) is a type of Coffin Siris Syndrome and it is also a category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is specifically characterized by global developmental delay and impaired intellectual development alongside hypotonia, feeding difficulties, and variable dysmorphic features, which are all due to a heterozygous mutation in the SMARCD1 gene located on chromosome 12q13.12.

Autosomal dominant auditory neuropathy 3, also precisely known as AUNA3, is categorized under autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness. This condition is defined as a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness characterized by progressive hearing loss with an inability to discern speech while maintaining sensitivity to sound, preservation of outer hair cell function, and either abnormal or absent auditory brainstem responses. The genetic foundation for autosomal dominant auditory neuropathy 3 is a heterozygous mutation in the TMEM43 gene located on chromosome 3p25.1. Furthermore, autosomal dominant auditory neuropathy 3 is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance, indicating its transmission pattern.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by muscular dystrophy resulting from defective glycosylation of dystroglycan. It has exact synonyms including CMD due to dystroglycanopathy, MDDG, and congenital muscular dystrophy due to dystroglycanopathy.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B is a specific type of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy. It is defined as a muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy that is characterized by the early onset of muscle weakness, intellectual disability in most cases, and the variable presence of mild brain anomalies. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with MDDGB.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b15 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined as a muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type B that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DPM3 gene located on chromosome 1q22. Additionally, muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b15 is exactly synonymous with MDDGB15 and congenital muscular dystrophy DPM3-related.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B14, also precisely known as MDDGB14 or congenital muscular dystrophy GMPPB-related, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, it is defined by a muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type B that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GMPPB gene located on chromosome 3p21.31.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B3, which has the exact synonyms MDDGB3 and congenital muscular dystrophy POMGNT1-related, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B and is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by a muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type B that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMGNT1 gene located on chromosome 1p34.1.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B4, also precisely known as MDDGB4 or congenital muscular dystrophy FKTN-related, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. This condition belongs to the broader category of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B and is characterized by muscular dystrophy resulting from impaired glycosylation of dystroglycan without intellectual impairment. It specifically arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FKTN gene located on chromosome 9q31.2. Furthermore, it is a manifestation of a disorder that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B2 (MDDGB2), also known as congenital muscular dystrophy POMT2-related, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. Specifically, it falls under the broader category of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B and is characterized by having its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B2 includes being a muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type B that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POMT2 gene located on chromosome 14q24.3.

Muscular Dystrophy Dystroglycanopathy Type C12 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy. It is characterized by congenital limb-girdle muscular dystrophy and cognitive impairment, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMK gene on chromosome 8p11.21. This condition is known by several exact synonyms including LGMD due to POMK deficiency, Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to POMK deficiency, MDDGC12, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy, limb-girdle, POMK-related.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type c8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy. It is characterized by being a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy is distinguished by an onset in childhood with a variable phenotype that ranges from mild intellectual disability and gait abnormalities to being asymptomatic, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMGNT2 gene on chromosome 3p22.1. It is known by several exact synonyms including LGMDR24, MDDGC2, autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 24, muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C, 8, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy, limb-girdle, POMGNT2-related.

Kinsship syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific kind of autosomal dominant disease that fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, seizures, mesomelic dysplasia, dysmorphic facial features, horseshoe or hypoplastic kidney, and failure to thrive, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the AFF3 gene located on chromosome 2q11.2. Moreover, Kinsship syndrome is also precisely known by several exact synonyms, including AFF3-related mesomelic dysplasia, KINS, and Steichen-Gersdorf type mesomelic dysplasia.

Multisystem proteinopathy is a type of motor neuron disease, which is defined as a motor neuron disease that has its material basis in some form of inheritance and affects the muscle, bone, and the nervous system.

Intestinal infectious disease is a type of intestinal disease and is defined as an intestinal disease that involves intestinal infection, which has a material basis in viruses, bacteria, fungi, and parasites. Additionally, it has the exact synonym bacterial enteritis.

Sensorineural hearing loss is a type of inner ear disease characterized by hearing loss resulting from damage to the cochlea, auditory nerve, and/or brainstem. It is also known by various exact synonyms including High Frequency Hearing Loss, High frequency deafness, Perceptive deafness, Perceptive hearing loss, Perceptive hearing loss or deafness, Sensorineural Deafness, Sensory hearing loss, central hearing loss, and high-frequency hearing loss. Additionally, sensorineural hearing loss has an exact match with MESH:D006319.

Thyroid lymphoma is a type of lymphoma and a type of thyroid cancer, characterized as a form of cancer of the thyroid gland that fundamentally originates from lymphocytes. It is also described as something that at least has a material basis in some lymphocytes.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 2B (MEN2B) is a specific type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the broader category of multiple endocrine neoplasia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. MEN2B is defined by the presence of medullary thyroid carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, multiple mucosal neuromas, and intestinal ganglioneuromas, often accompanied by a marfanoid habitus and other skeletal abnormalities. It is known by several exact synonyms, including MEN Type IIB, MEN2B, Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia, Type 3, Wagenmann-Froboese syndrome, and Mucosal Neuroma Syndrome.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 1 (MEN Type 1), also known precisely as MEN Type I, Wermer Syndrome, and Wermer's Syndrome, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of multiple endocrine neoplasia. It is defined as a multiple endocrine neoplasia that originates from a mutation in the MEN1 tumor suppressor gene, characterized by overactive endocrine glands often involving tumors of the parathyroid glands, the pituitary gland, and the pancreas. Furthermore, it is a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.
Endometritis is a type of endometrial disease that is characterized by inflammation of the endometrium. It is also defined as a condition that involves at least some inflammation.

Ampulla of Vater cancer is the same as a disease that is both a type of cancer and is located in the hepatopancreatic ampulla. It is a type of duodenum cancer and also a type of bile duct cancer. Ampulla of Vater cancer is defined as a duodenum cancer located in the ampulla of Vater. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: malignant tumor of the ampulla of Vater.

Duodenum cancer, which is the same as something that intersects with cancer and a disease located in the duodenum, is a type of small intestine cancer and also considered a type of duodenum disease. It is defined as a small intestine cancer located in the beginning section of the small intestine. Furthermore, duodenum cancer is exactly synonymous with duodenal cancer, cancer of the duodenum, and duodenal neoplasm.

The ampulla of Vater benign neoplasm is equivalent to an intersection of benign neoplasms and diseases that are located in the hepatopancreatic ampulla. It is classified as a type of biliary tract benign neoplasm, a type of duodenal benign neoplasm, and a type of bile duct disease. The definition of an ampulla of Vater benign neoplasm is a duodenal benign neoplasm located in the ampulla of Vater. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with a tumor of the ampulla of Vater.

Migraine with aura is a type of migraine that is defined as a migraine characterized by a headache which is preceded or accompanied by a transient focal neurological phenomenon. It is also exactly synonymous with classic migraine.

Tabes dorsalis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis, which is also known by its exact synonyms, Posterior spinal sclerosis and Tabes dorsalis - neurosyphilis. This condition is characterized by a slow degeneration of the nerve cells and nerve fibers that carry sensory information to the brain. Specifically, Tabes dorsalis manifests through several symptoms including intense, stabbing pain in the back and legs that recurs irregularly, gait ataxia, hyperesthesia, paresthesia, loss of bladder sensation leading to urine retention, and erectile dysfunction. Additionally, it is noted for having at least some symptoms such as ataxia, hyperesthesia, and paresthesia.

Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is a type of bacterial infectious disease and a type of disease affecting the female reproductive system, which at least has a material basis in some bacteria. It is defined as a female reproductive system disease characterized by an infection of the female reproductive organs. Additionally, PID is the exact synonym for pelvic inflammatory disease.

Pulmonary interstitial emphysema is a type of pulmonary emphysema, which is defined as a pulmonary emphysema characterized by the abnormal location of gas within the pulmonary interstitium and lymphatics, usually due to positive pressure ventilation.

Compensatory emphysema is a type of pulmonary emphysema that is characterized by the overinflation of part of a lung. This overinflation occurs in response to either the surgical removal of another part of the lung or a decrease in size of another part of the lung.
Hyperlucent lung is a type of lung disease, which is defined as a lung disease characterized by increased lucency compared to the other lung on a chest radiograph or CT.

Cycloplegia is a type of eye accommodation disease characterized by paralysis of the ciliary muscle of the eye, resulting in a loss of accommodation. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Ciliary muscle paresis, Cycloplegic paralysis of accommodation, and Paresis of accommodation.
Eye accommodation disease is a type of eye disease. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by a decreased ability to change the optical power of the eye to maintain a clear image.

Asymptomatic neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis, which is characterized by resulting in mild meningitis. It is a condition that falls into the category of diseases that, at the very least, exhibit some symptoms of meningitis.

Late congenital syphilis is a specific type of congenital syphilis that manifests in children aged two years or older, who acquired the infection trans-placentally. This form of syphilis is characterized by several key aspects. Firstly, it is transmitted primarily through placental transmission. Additionally, it is grounded in abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth. The disease is notable for its symptoms, which include optic atrophy and interstitial keratitis among others. Specifically, late congenital syphilis presents with a range of symptoms such as gummatous ulcers, periosteal lesions, paresis, tabes, optic atrophy, interstitial keratitis, sensorineural deafness, and dental deformities. Furthermore, late congenital syphilis is also known by the exact synonym juvenile neurosyphilis.
Malignant eyelid melanoma is a type of skin melanoma and it is defined as a skin melanoma that arises from the upper or lower eyelid.

Dysplastic Nevus Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which inherently relies on autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by the presence of multiple dysplastic nevi (atypical moles) and a history of melanoma in two family members. Furthermore, Dysplastic Nevus Syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: FAMM syndrome and familial atypical multiple mole-melanoma. Additionally, it has an exact match with the MESH identifier D004416.
Balloon cell malignant melanoma is a type of skin melanoma characterized by the presence of nodules containing large melanoma cells with clear, foamy, or finely vacuolated cytoplasm.

Nodular malignant melanoma is a type of skin melanoma that is characterized as highly aggressive and manifests as a uniform blue-black, blue-red, or amelanotic nodule. It is also known by its exact synonym, nodular melanoma.
Endometrial disease is a type of uterine disease, which is defined as a uterine disease that is located in the endometrium.

Skin amelanotic melanoma is a type of skin melanoma that is characterized by a lack of melanin pigment in most of the melanoma tumor cells. It is also exactly synonymous with skin amelanotic malignant melanoma.

A subglottis benign neoplasm is the same as something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease with a location in the subglottis. It is a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm and is defined as a laryngeal benign neoplasm located in the subglottic area of the larynx. Additionally, subglottis benign neoplasm has an exact synonym: Subglottic tumor.

Larynx leiomyoma is a type of leiomyoma and a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm, which is something that at least derives from some smooth muscle cell. It is defined as a laryngeal benign neoplasm that derives from smooth muscle cells.

Larynx squamous papilloma is a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm, which is also known as Laryngeal Squamous Cell Papilloma. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core covered by stratified squamous epithelium and manifests at least one symptom, hoarseness.

Syphilitic meningitis is a type of bacterial meningitis that is characterized by inflammation of the tissues covering the brain and spinal cord. It is transmitted by contact and has inflammation as a symptom.

Hymenolepiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease and is also known exactly as Hymenolepis infectious disease and dwarf tapeworm infection. It involves infection of the bowel by Hymenolepis nana or Hymenolepis diminuta, with its material basis in some Hymenolepis flatworms. The symptoms of hymenolepiasis include weakness, diarrhea, gastrointestinal discomfort, itchy anus, poor appetite, and weakness.

Diphyllobothriasis, also known as Diphyllobothrium infection or fish tapeworm, is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease and has an exact match with MESH:D004169. This disease fundamentally has its material basis in Dibothriocephalus latus and manifests through various symptoms such as weight loss, abdominal discomfort, diarrhea, and vomiting. Additionally, it features significant conditions like vitamin B12 deficiency and pernicious anemia. Its definition elaborates on it being a parasitic infection caused by Diphyllobothrium latum, which occurs due to the consumption of raw or undercooked fish, leading to symptoms including abdominal discomfort, diarrhea, vomiting, weight loss, and specifically vitamin B12 deficiency accompanied by pernicious anemia.

Cysticercosis is a type of taeniasis, as well as a type of muscular, heart, central nervous system, skin, and eye disease. It is characterized by being an intersection of diseases that affect various body zones, specifically the skin, heart, eye, central nervous system, and muscle tissue. Cysticercosis is defined as a taeniasis that results from the ingestion of eggs or larvae of the Taenia solium tapeworm found in undercooked pork or fecally contaminated food or water. This leads to infections in the central nervous system, heart, muscles, subcutaneous tissues, and eyes. Notably, neurocysticercosis, a manifestation of the disease, can cause seizures, mental disturbances, focal neurological deficits, and intracerebral lesions. Cysticercosis is also known by several exact synonyms, including Pork tapeworm infection, Tapeworm infection intestinal taenia solum, Tapeworm infection pork, Intestinal taenia solium infection, Neurocysticercosis, and Tenia solium infectious disease.

Sparganosis is identified as a type of disease that affects multiple body systems and structures, including the urinary system, inner ear, breast, lung, and brain. It is also categorized as a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease. The condition is characterized by being a parasitic infection caused by the genus Spirometra, leading to the development of a painful nodule after the plerocercoid larvae migrate to various body locations such as the brain, which results in cerebral sparganosis, as well as subcutaneous tissue, breast, orbit, urinary tract, pleural cavity, lungs, abdominal viscera, and inner ear. Sparganosis is synonymously known as Infection by Sparganum and has an exact match in the medical subject headings (MESH) with the identifier D013031.

Syphilitic encephalitis is a type of encephalitis and also a type of condition that is transmitted by some form of contact transmission. Furthermore, it is defined as an encephalitis that has its material basis in a central neural system infection caused by Treponema pallidum.

Gastric leiomyoma is a type of gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm and has an exact synonym, leiomyoma of the stomach. It is defined as a gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, interlacing fascicles, and a whorled pattern.
An intracranial abscess is a type of central nervous system disease that is defined as a disease located in the skull and is characterized by a collection of pus (infected material) inside the skull.

Sleeping sickness, also known as African sleeping sickness or African trypanosomiasis, is a type of trypanosomiasis. It results from infection by Trypanosoma brucei and gambiense, transmitted through the bite of an infected tsetse fly (Glossina spp). The disease is characterized by a variety of symptoms, including ataxia, confusion, joint pain, itching, headache, sleep disturbances, fever, and sensory disturbances. These symptoms encompass fever, headache, joint pain, itching, confusion, sensory disturbances, poor coordination, and sleep disturbances, as detailed in its definition.

Trypanosomiasis is a type of parasitic protozoa infectious disease, which specifically involves infection caused by parasitic protozoan of the genus Trypanosoma in animals and humans. Additionally, trypanosomiasis is characterized as a condition that at least has its material basis in some Trypanosoma.

Hyperpigmentation of the eyelid is a type of pigmentation disease, eyelid disease, and a condition that affects at least some part of the eyelid. It is defined as an eyelid disease characterized by dark eyelids. Additionally, hyperpigmentation of the eyelid is exactly synonymous with "dark eyelids" and "dyspigmentation of eyelid."
Pigmentation disease is a type of skin disease that is characterized by the discoloration of the skin.

Corneal disease is the same as something that is both a disease and has a location in the cornea, signifying an intersection between diseases and conditions specifically located in the cornea. Additionally, corneal disease falls under the broader category of eye diseases. It is defined as an eye disease that affects the cornea, the transparent surface of the eye responsible for assisting in light refraction.

Acute hydrops keratoconus is a type of keratoconus characterized by stromal edema due to leakage of aqueous humor through a tear in Descemet's membrane. It is also exactly synonymous with Keratoconus, acute hydrops.

Keratoconus is a type of corneal disease and has a definition as a corneal disease characterized by structural changes within the cornea, causing it to thin and change, leading to a protruding conical shape. It also has the exact synonym "conical cornea."

Cerebral artery occlusion is a type of cerebrovascular disease and is characterized by a blockage in one or more of the cerebral arteries. This condition is also classified under diseases that have their location in the cerebrum.
Venous insufficiency is a type of vein disease characterized by impaired flow of blood through the veins, and it is also exactly synonymous with peripheral venous insufficiency.

Psychologic vaginismus is a type of psychosexual disorder that is defined as a psychosexual disorder characterized by involuntary spasm of the outer muscles of the vagina during penetration that results from a psychological cause. It has exact synonyms including Functional vaginismus, Non-organic vaginismus, and Psychogenic Vaginismus.
Psychosexual disorder is a type of sexual health disorder, defined as a sexual problem that is psychological, rather than physiological in origin.

Xerophthalmia is a type of dry eye syndrome and is defined as a dry eye syndrome characterized by conjunctival and corneal xerosis, Bitot's spots, keratomalacia, nyctalopia, and retinopathy resulting from vitamin A deficiency. It also has an exact synonym, Conjunctival xerosis.

Conjunctival degeneration is the same as an intersection of an eye degenerative disease and a disease that at least has its location in the conjunctiva. It is a type of conjunctival disease as well as a type of eye degenerative disease.

Dry eye syndrome is a type of lacrimal apparatus disease characterized by persistent irritation or burning of the corneal surface. It is also known as tear film insufficiency or dry eye disease. Furthermore, dry eye syndrome has an exact match in the MESH database with the identifier D015352.

Thymus lymphoma is a type of lymphoma and also a type of thymus cancer, which is characterized by having a material basis in some lymphocyte. It is defined as a thymus cancer that arises from the thymus.

Long bones of lower limb cancer is a type of bone cancer that has a definition stating it is a bone cancer manifested in the long bones of the lower limb. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is malignant neoplasm of long bones of the leg.

Malignant neoplasm of short bones of lower limb is a type of bone cancer, which is defined as a bone cancer that is located in the short bones of lower limbs. It has exact synonyms including malignant neoplasm of short bone of lower limb and malignant neoplasm of short bones of leg.

Meckel's diverticulum cancer is a type of ileum cancer, which is also known for being a disease that occurs in the ileum. It is defined as an ileum cancer originating from Meckel's diverticulum. Furthermore, Meckel's diverticulum cancer is exactly synonymous with Meckel diverticulum cancer and malignant neoplasm of Meckel's diverticulum.

Ileum cancer, also known as ileal neoplasm or malignant neoplasm of ileum, is a type of cancer that intersects with conditions that are both a cancer and a disease located in the ileum. It is a specific form of small intestine cancer characterized by its location in the ileum. The definition of ileum cancer is a small intestine cancer that is located in the ileum.

Small intestine cancer is identical to a condition that is both a type of cancer and a disease located in the small intestine. It is a specific type of intestinal cancer. Furthermore, small intestine cancer is defined as an intestinal cancer that is located in the small intestine.

Intestinal cancer, which is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer and also a type of intestinal disease, is defined as a gastrointestinal system cancer located in the intestine. This cancer is synonymous with malignant intestinal tumors and malignant neoplasm of the intestine. Furthermore, intestinal cancer is the same as something that intersects with both cancer and a disease, specifically one that is located in the intestine.

Benign ileal neoplasm is equivalent to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease located at least in the ileum. It is a subtype of small intestine benign neoplasm and is defined as a small intestine benign neoplasm that affects the wall of the ileum. Additionally, benign ileal neoplasm is exactly synonymous with Ileal tumor.

Osteonecrosis is a type of ischemic bone disease and something that at least has the symptom of some necrosis. It is defined as an ischemic bone disease that results in necrosis located in bone. Furthermore, osteonecrosis is exactly synonymous with avascular necrosis of bone, aseptic necrosis, and bone necrosis.
Lacrimal passage granuloma, which has the exact synonym "Granuloma of lacrimal passages," is a type of lacrimal apparatus disease.

Optic papillitis is a type of optic neuritis and has an exact synonym, papillitis. It is defined as an optic neuritis characterized by hyperemia, blurring of the disk margins, microhemorrhages, blind spot enlargement, and engorgement of retinal veins, resulting in swelling around the optic disc.

Neuroretinitis is a type of eye disease and is defined as an eye disease characterized by inflammation of the retina. It has exact synonyms including Focal retinitis and retinochoroiditis, juxtapapillary, juxtapapillary focal retinitis and retinochoroiditis, as well as Papilloretinitis.
Malignant hypertensive renal disease is a type of renal hypertension and is also a type of condition that affects the kidney.

Endobronchial lipoma is a type of lipoma, a type of bronchial benign neoplasm, and a type of entity that at least derives from some adipocyte. It is defined as a lipoma that is located within the lumen of a bronchus.
Spindle cell lipoma is a type of lipoma, defined as an asymptomatic, slow-growing subcutaneous tumor that has a predilection for the posterior back, neck, and shoulders of older men.

Esophageal lipoma is a type of gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm, lipoma, and esophageal disease. It originates from adipocytes and is located in the esophagus. It is defined as a lipoma located in the esophagus and is also known as Lipoma of the esophagus.

Skin lipoma is a type of skin benign neoplasm, lipoma, and something that at least derives from some adipocyte. It is defined as a skin benign neoplasm that derives from fat cells. Skin lipoma has exact synonyms including Cutaneous Lipoma, Lipoma of Skin, cutaneous lipomatous tumor, and lipoma of face.

Osteomyelitis is a type of bone inflammation disease characterized by being a bacterial and fungal infectious disease. It is defined as a bone inflammation disease that has a material basis in infection located in the bone or bone marrow. This infection is due to bacteria and fungi.

Liver lipoma is a type of lipoma, and it is also considered a type of liver benign neoplasm. Additionally, it is classified as something that at least derives from some adipocyte. It is defined as a lipoma located in the liver. Liver lipoma is exactly synonymous with Lipoma of the Liver and hepatic lipoma.
Pleomorphic lipoma is a type of lipoma, defined as a lipoma that is characterized by floret giant cells with overlapping nuclei.
